00:00:23.070 --> 00:00:25.570
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Tonight is
a deep dive into DARPA, which

00:00:25.570 --> 00:00:29.880
is a very different model.

00:00:29.880 --> 00:00:34.190
And we've talked
around DARPA, but--

00:00:34.190 --> 00:00:36.130
we talked about snippets
of some of the stuff

00:00:36.130 --> 00:00:38.350
that we're going to
be going through,

00:00:38.350 --> 00:00:40.480
but tonight will be
kind of a deep dive

00:00:40.480 --> 00:00:43.600
into looking this model.

00:00:43.600 --> 00:00:45.250
And the model is
an important one

00:00:45.250 --> 00:00:50.020
because we've gotten
so much out of DARPA.

00:00:50.020 --> 00:00:52.900
It's been a remarkable run.

00:00:52.900 --> 00:00:58.620
And so we'll look at
the foundational period.

00:00:58.620 --> 00:01:00.620
And there are a lot of
good MIT stories in here,

00:01:00.620 --> 00:01:03.820
which we'll get on the table.

00:01:03.820 --> 00:01:08.020
But we'll also try
to frame really

00:01:08.020 --> 00:01:13.580
how this organization,
institution functions.

00:01:13.580 --> 00:01:18.440
So this is a JCR
Licklider story--

00:01:18.440 --> 00:01:21.610
one of MIT's all-time greats.

00:01:21.610 --> 00:01:26.530
And he doesn't get talked
about that much at MIT,

00:01:26.530 --> 00:01:29.020
but he really is foundational.

00:01:29.020 --> 00:01:40.870
And he comes in at a time when
computing is really completely

00:01:40.870 --> 00:01:42.670
different than it
is today, and is

00:01:42.670 --> 00:01:49.240
able, with his team at DARPA,
to really work through--

00:01:49.240 --> 00:01:52.840
really in an intergenerational
between DARPA program manager

00:01:52.840 --> 00:01:55.390
and office director
generations--

00:01:55.390 --> 00:01:59.070
really rework the entire sector.

00:01:59.070 --> 00:02:03.100
So we've talked a little about
Whirlwind and SAGE earlier.

00:02:03.100 --> 00:02:07.000
And just to remind
you, this was one

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:09.220
of the foundational
early computer systems.

00:02:09.220 --> 00:02:12.790
This was MIT's at
Whirlwind and SAGE.

00:02:12.790 --> 00:02:16.960
And this is Jay Forrester, and
he's holding the magnetic core

00:02:16.960 --> 00:02:20.290
memory that he and one
of his graduate students

00:02:20.290 --> 00:02:22.840
came up with, which enabled
real-time computing,

00:02:22.840 --> 00:02:25.210
a really critical advance.

00:02:25.210 --> 00:02:30.970
And you start to see at
Whirlwind, in the upper-left--

00:02:30.970 --> 00:02:33.700
which merges into
the SAGE system--

00:02:33.700 --> 00:02:36.400
you start to see where
computing is going.

00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:45.230
So that picture of
this computer operator,

00:02:45.230 --> 00:02:47.960
this lady sitting in front of a
keyboard in front of a cathode

00:02:47.960 --> 00:02:50.480
ray screen.

00:02:50.480 --> 00:02:53.600
That's this, and there it is.

00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:59.480
There it is at late '40s, early
'50s when this is going on.

00:02:59.480 --> 00:03:03.530
And how did this all evolve?

00:03:03.530 --> 00:03:06.080
So on the lower left
is George Valley,

00:03:06.080 --> 00:03:07.870
who was an MIT faculty member.

00:03:07.870 --> 00:03:10.520
He was part of the Rad Lab.

00:03:10.520 --> 00:03:14.120
And Valley is on a scientific
advisory board to the Air

00:03:14.120 --> 00:03:18.620
Force, and he sounds the
alarm, essentially alerting

00:03:18.620 --> 00:03:22.820
the Air Force and frankly,
the military in general,

00:03:22.820 --> 00:03:29.280
that the Soviet Union has
developed a long-range bombing

00:03:29.280 --> 00:03:29.820
aircraft.

00:03:29.820 --> 00:03:32.340
They have nuclear weapons,
and they have, therefore,

00:03:32.340 --> 00:03:34.140
first strike capability.

00:03:34.140 --> 00:03:37.440
There is absolutely
nothing in their way

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:40.140
of reaching the northern
part of the United States.

00:03:40.140 --> 00:03:43.620
And that's a terrifying
realization moment.

00:03:43.620 --> 00:03:48.100
So Valley gets the Air Force
mobilized around an air defense

00:03:48.100 --> 00:03:49.140
mission.

00:03:49.140 --> 00:03:52.440
And computers are going
to be at the heart of it.

00:03:52.440 --> 00:03:54.060
And he goes to
Jay Forrester, who

00:03:54.060 --> 00:03:58.560
was developing this Whirlwind
system for the Navy.

00:03:58.560 --> 00:04:01.590
The Navy's is
canceling Whirlwind,

00:04:01.590 --> 00:04:04.500
so Valley just moves
Forrester and the team,

00:04:04.500 --> 00:04:10.980
and the Whirlwind system over to
the SAGE project of developing

00:04:10.980 --> 00:04:13.410
an air defense and controllers.

00:04:13.410 --> 00:04:16.380
And the picture here is what--

00:04:16.380 --> 00:04:17.940
essentially what
the picture looks

00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:20.010
like of all these
different defense

00:04:20.010 --> 00:04:25.350
systems, from early missiles,
and artillery, and fighter

00:04:25.350 --> 00:04:31.120
aircraft, all being linked into
a communications and computer

00:04:31.120 --> 00:04:31.620
system.

00:04:31.620 --> 00:04:35.490
And then fascinatingly,
the communications lines

00:04:35.490 --> 00:04:38.310
are across phone lines.

00:04:38.310 --> 00:04:41.430
So the computers are running a
communication system that comes

00:04:41.430 --> 00:04:44.040
into them across phone lines.

00:04:44.040 --> 00:04:49.930
The picture of those
Air Force airmen

00:04:49.930 --> 00:04:51.910
sitting in front of
cathode ray screens,

00:04:51.910 --> 00:04:55.030
they're holding
this peculiar thing.

00:04:55.030 --> 00:04:55.930
It's a light gun.

00:04:55.930 --> 00:04:57.910
It's the mouse.

00:04:57.910 --> 00:05:00.940
So you start to see these iconic
pictures of where all this

00:05:00.940 --> 00:05:04.120
stuff that we just live with--

00:05:04.120 --> 00:05:05.920
where it all starts-- come from.

00:05:05.920 --> 00:05:11.530
And a lot of it came from the
Whirlwind and SAGE systems.

00:05:11.530 --> 00:05:13.960
MIT doesn't want to go into
the business of manufacturing

00:05:13.960 --> 00:05:14.560
computers.

00:05:14.560 --> 00:05:19.000
They make the initial
computers for the SAGE system,

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:21.370
but they don't want to be in
the computer manufacturing

00:05:21.370 --> 00:05:22.540
business.

00:05:22.540 --> 00:05:29.710
So the SAGE system becomes
the IBM 700 series.

00:05:29.710 --> 00:05:33.580
This is how IBM really
starts to scale up

00:05:33.580 --> 00:05:35.380
in mainframe
computing, and starts

00:05:35.380 --> 00:05:38.810
building the computing systems
for this air defense system.

00:05:38.810 --> 00:05:42.100
So again, it's an example of
long-term patient military

00:05:42.100 --> 00:05:44.200
support for
technology development

00:05:44.200 --> 00:05:45.760
that we've seen before.

00:05:45.760 --> 00:05:48.010
And here it is again,
only this time,

00:05:48.010 --> 00:05:49.240
it's sponsoring computing.

00:05:49.240 --> 00:05:53.830
So Mitch Waldrop's book
The Dream Machine I think

00:05:53.830 --> 00:05:58.780
is really the classic on the
evolution of the Information

00:05:58.780 --> 00:05:59.860
Age.

00:05:59.860 --> 00:06:03.370
It is full of wonderful
stories, and I

00:06:03.370 --> 00:06:04.880
feel that it's
really well written,

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:07.160
and I couldn't resist
giving you a big dose of it.

00:06:07.160 --> 00:06:10.127
But there's a lot of great
MIT stories in here, but lots

00:06:10.127 --> 00:06:12.460
of great stories about the
foundation of where computing

00:06:12.460 --> 00:06:14.470
came from and how it arrived--

00:06:14.470 --> 00:06:17.860
that fits with the material that
we've been covering in class.

00:06:17.860 --> 00:06:20.170
So we'll go through
some of this key stuff,

00:06:20.170 --> 00:06:24.310
and then stuff will
lead us in some Q and A.

00:06:24.310 --> 00:06:30.910
Computing before Licklider, it's
non-interactive, it's not fun,

00:06:30.910 --> 00:06:32.500
it's not exciting.

00:06:32.500 --> 00:06:36.040
It's behind glass
walls, and you'd

00:06:36.040 --> 00:06:40.330
be met by like these high
priests and priestesses who are

00:06:40.330 --> 00:06:44.380
wearing white coats and gloves.

00:06:44.380 --> 00:06:50.260
And you'd carry your
stack of punch cards in,

00:06:50.260 --> 00:06:54.100
and you'd hand over this
offering of punch cards.

00:06:54.100 --> 00:06:55.527
Maybe the high
priest or priestess

00:06:55.527 --> 00:06:57.610
paid attention to you, and
took the cards from you

00:06:57.610 --> 00:06:58.570
in a few minutes.

00:06:58.570 --> 00:07:00.040
Maybe that happened.

00:07:00.040 --> 00:07:03.430
And then they would
tell you, fine.

00:07:03.430 --> 00:07:07.060
You're 479th on line,
come back in a week

00:07:07.060 --> 00:07:09.100
and we'll have run this for you.

00:07:09.100 --> 00:07:12.520
This is not real-time computing.

00:07:12.520 --> 00:07:13.990
That's literally
the way was like.

00:07:13.990 --> 00:07:15.490
It was just very forbidding.

00:07:15.490 --> 00:07:16.360
It was very distant.

00:07:18.970 --> 00:07:23.240
It's definitely not
what we have now.

00:07:23.240 --> 00:07:26.050
And it's built for a number
of processing bureaucracies,

00:07:26.050 --> 00:07:31.432
and initially in government,
but then in business.

00:07:31.432 --> 00:07:32.890
And that's not to
knock mainframes.

00:07:32.890 --> 00:07:37.600
They're a huge remarkable
technical advance.

00:07:37.600 --> 00:07:41.110
IBM starts to
dominate that sector,

00:07:41.110 --> 00:07:44.230
and they incorporate
the machinery

00:07:44.230 --> 00:07:47.680
that they're familiar with.

00:07:47.680 --> 00:07:49.750
They're building
business machines that

00:07:49.750 --> 00:07:53.120
are punch card-run
with batch processing,

00:07:53.120 --> 00:07:59.050
so they carry those technologies
into the mainframe computers

00:07:59.050 --> 00:08:00.190
that they're building.

00:08:00.190 --> 00:08:03.960
Now, look, you come
back after a week,

00:08:03.960 --> 00:08:07.570
and you get handed a stack
of this weird green and white

00:08:07.570 --> 00:08:09.288
paper with holes
punched in the side.

00:08:09.288 --> 00:08:11.080
You probably don't have
any memory of this,

00:08:11.080 --> 00:08:12.910
but I remember it deeply.

00:08:12.910 --> 00:08:15.088
And you'd get handed
this stack of paper,

00:08:15.088 --> 00:08:16.630
and then you'd go
back to your office

00:08:16.630 --> 00:08:19.510
and you sit down and
start go through.

00:08:19.510 --> 00:08:23.680
And then you realize
that, after page 39,

00:08:23.680 --> 00:08:26.680
it's all gibberish, because
one of your punch cards

00:08:26.680 --> 00:08:30.010
was out of order or upside-down,
or something like that.

00:08:30.010 --> 00:08:32.012
So then you'd have to go
back and stand in line

00:08:32.012 --> 00:08:33.429
with the high
priest or priestess,

00:08:33.429 --> 00:08:35.740
and start the whole
process all over again.

00:08:35.740 --> 00:08:38.559
That's really what it's like.

00:08:38.559 --> 00:08:43.090
And the emphasis was on
bigger and bigger computers

00:08:43.090 --> 00:08:50.450
able to handle more and more
large number batch processing.

00:08:50.450 --> 00:08:55.960
So Licklider comes
along more than a decade

00:08:55.960 --> 00:09:03.610
before personal computing and
30 years before the internet.

00:09:03.610 --> 00:09:06.400
And the word computer
still has this kind

00:09:06.400 --> 00:09:11.170
of ominous tone of a
intimidating device that's

00:09:11.170 --> 00:09:15.190
kind of hidden away in
this over-lit, super air

00:09:15.190 --> 00:09:19.750
conditioned, noisy,
fan-ridden space.

00:09:19.750 --> 00:09:25.570
And it's about as far away
from this as we can imagine.

00:09:25.570 --> 00:09:30.550
And this is really what that
team at DARPA, that Licklider

00:09:30.550 --> 00:09:33.250
led, drives us to.

00:09:33.250 --> 00:09:36.070
So we'll talk about
the film in a bit,

00:09:36.070 --> 00:09:39.040
but a lot of the
leadership of that team

00:09:39.040 --> 00:09:40.480
goes on to do amazing stuff.

00:09:40.480 --> 00:09:43.930
So here's some
Licklider photographs.

00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:52.210
This is DEC's PDP-8 that
was the first mini-computer,

00:09:52.210 --> 00:09:57.340
an entire movement away
from mainframe computing

00:09:57.340 --> 00:09:59.800
that really was key to
spawning the revolution.

00:09:59.800 --> 00:10:03.010
So Licklider is playing
with this machine.

00:10:03.010 --> 00:10:05.170
It came from Digital
Equipment Corporation,

00:10:05.170 --> 00:10:09.010
which is an MIT spin-off,
Lincoln Labs spin-off.

00:10:09.010 --> 00:10:10.630
And they're trying
to start to pursue

00:10:10.630 --> 00:10:13.060
a more personalized
kind of computing

00:10:13.060 --> 00:10:16.330
with these mini-computers.

00:10:16.330 --> 00:10:23.260
On the lower left is the
team that does the internet.

00:10:26.200 --> 00:10:30.400
And the only book
that Licklider wrote

00:10:30.400 --> 00:10:33.520
is called libraries
of the future,

00:10:33.520 --> 00:10:39.900
and he essentially envisions
digital storage of everything.

00:10:39.900 --> 00:10:42.082
It's amazing work.

00:10:42.082 --> 00:10:43.540
The librarians are
trying to wonder

00:10:43.540 --> 00:10:45.430
what to do with computers,
and he essentially

00:10:45.430 --> 00:10:49.000
gives them the entire picture.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:51.430
So a very innovative character.

00:10:54.160 --> 00:10:55.900
He grows up in St. Louis.

00:10:55.900 --> 00:11:04.840
Both his parents are ministers,
and he's an only child.

00:11:04.840 --> 00:11:08.740
Responsible kid,
but his parents let

00:11:08.740 --> 00:11:14.740
him do things like assemble
automobiles in the living room.

00:11:14.740 --> 00:11:17.920
For most of his life, he never
spent more than $50 on a car

00:11:17.920 --> 00:11:21.760
because he would essentially
by junkers and parts

00:11:21.760 --> 00:11:23.120
and put them together himself.

00:11:23.120 --> 00:11:25.330
That's the way the
family drove around.

00:11:25.330 --> 00:11:28.630
So he has a tremendous
facility for--

00:11:28.630 --> 00:11:32.780
remember we talked
about mind in hand,

00:11:32.780 --> 00:11:35.200
when we talked about the
Industrial Revolution.

00:11:35.200 --> 00:11:39.730
Licklider has got that
tactile knowledge facility,

00:11:39.730 --> 00:11:42.130
and it's part of why
he loves computers.

00:11:42.130 --> 00:11:46.270
He falls in love with
psychology and becomes actually

00:11:46.270 --> 00:11:49.420
quite a significant early
thinker about psychology,

00:11:49.420 --> 00:11:51.930
when that whole field
is starting to change.

00:11:51.930 --> 00:11:55.750
His World War II
experience is spent up

00:11:55.750 --> 00:12:01.030
at Memorial Hall at
Harvard in the basement

00:12:01.030 --> 00:12:05.860
with acoustics
researchers, studying

00:12:05.860 --> 00:12:12.280
how pilots and the crew of
airplanes-- how they react

00:12:12.280 --> 00:12:14.320
to this unbelievable
noise that they've

00:12:14.320 --> 00:12:17.580
got in the pre-pressurized
cabins in World War II aircraft

00:12:17.580 --> 00:12:20.770
with these huge propeller
engines next to their ears,

00:12:20.770 --> 00:12:22.660
trying to hear radio signals.

00:12:22.660 --> 00:12:26.440
And this is before there's
any kind of navigation system.

00:12:26.440 --> 00:12:27.520
It's pre-LORAN.

00:12:27.520 --> 00:12:29.320
It's obviously long before GPS.

00:12:29.320 --> 00:12:32.630
So there's a terrible problem--
the communication systems

00:12:32.630 --> 00:12:34.387
and the way in which
you navigate a lot--

00:12:34.387 --> 00:12:35.970
typically, if you
can't see the stars.

00:12:35.970 --> 00:12:39.280
So all kinds of plans
get lost over oceans

00:12:39.280 --> 00:12:43.720
because the radio communications
don't get picked up.

00:12:43.720 --> 00:12:48.580
So he's working on how can
we improve the man machine

00:12:48.580 --> 00:12:52.840
interface around acoustics
in the cabin of airplanes?

00:12:52.840 --> 00:12:58.360
So he's thinking a lot about
how people and machines work

00:12:58.360 --> 00:12:59.900
together.

00:12:59.900 --> 00:13:03.370
And that's what he contributes.

00:13:03.370 --> 00:13:05.740
He's not a computer-- early
computer scientists really,

00:13:05.740 --> 00:13:06.640
although he loves computing.

00:13:06.640 --> 00:13:07.960
He plays with them all
the time, knows them

00:13:07.960 --> 00:13:09.280
backwards and forwards.

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:15.520
He's bringing the ideas of
a psychologist to computing,

00:13:15.520 --> 00:13:17.260
and that's what,
in many ways, makes

00:13:17.260 --> 00:13:19.690
him a complete
breakthrough thinker.

00:13:19.690 --> 00:13:22.120
He's able to take
ideas from psychology

00:13:22.120 --> 00:13:25.673
and bring them into this early
computing field, not just

00:13:25.673 --> 00:13:27.340
an engineering
perspective-- although he

00:13:27.340 --> 00:13:30.730
has very good engineering
and physics capability.

00:13:30.730 --> 00:13:38.710
And he writes an absolutely
seminal article in 1960

00:13:38.710 --> 00:13:41.440
that essentially was still
working through his agenda

00:13:41.440 --> 00:13:43.480
of what needs to happen.

00:13:43.480 --> 00:13:48.970
It's an amazing vision.

00:13:48.970 --> 00:13:52.210
He, for example, realizes
that 85% of human time

00:13:52.210 --> 00:13:55.750
is spent getting
into a position to be

00:13:55.750 --> 00:13:58.550
able to think about a problem--
arranging all the stuff,

00:13:58.550 --> 00:13:59.967
pulling all the
material together,

00:13:59.967 --> 00:14:01.460
and then you can think.

00:14:01.460 --> 00:14:04.550
Suppose you could reduce that
85% by having the computer

00:14:04.550 --> 00:14:06.470
do it for you, by having
the computer arrange

00:14:06.470 --> 00:14:08.480
a lot of that stuff for you.

00:14:08.480 --> 00:14:10.490
That's part of his concept.

00:14:10.490 --> 00:14:13.010
The central concept
he has is the hope

00:14:13.010 --> 00:14:15.590
is that human
brains and computing

00:14:15.590 --> 00:14:18.350
machines will be coupled
together very tightly,

00:14:18.350 --> 00:14:20.660
and that the resulting
partnership will

00:14:20.660 --> 00:14:23.990
think as no human is
ever thought and process

00:14:23.990 --> 00:14:26.690
data in a way not approached
by the information handling

00:14:26.690 --> 00:14:29.270
machines we have today.

00:14:29.270 --> 00:14:30.860
In other words,
he has this vision

00:14:30.860 --> 00:14:34.100
of people and machines in this
collaborative relationship.

00:14:34.100 --> 00:14:37.167
It's going to be a symbiotic
kind of relationship.

00:14:37.167 --> 00:14:38.750
And let's think for
a minute about how

00:14:38.750 --> 00:14:40.940
people thought about computing.

00:14:40.940 --> 00:14:44.150
Now, we're all sitting around
wondering when the robots are

00:14:44.150 --> 00:14:45.800
going to take our jobs.

00:14:45.800 --> 00:14:49.010
That's the obsession
of the moment.

00:14:49.010 --> 00:14:50.690
Licklider's coming
out of a time period

00:14:50.690 --> 00:14:52.580
where there was a
similar obsession.

00:14:52.580 --> 00:14:55.190
And Norbert Wiener-- who
pops up in this book,

00:14:55.190 --> 00:14:57.500
and is another one of
MIT's absolute greats,

00:14:57.500 --> 00:15:00.200
a brilliant mathematician--

00:15:00.200 --> 00:15:03.530
Wiener is the one who
invents the term cybernetics.

00:15:03.530 --> 00:15:08.407
And Wiener has this
vision saying, look out--

00:15:08.407 --> 00:15:09.740
and he writes in the late '40s--

00:15:09.740 --> 00:15:12.380
the computers are
coming, and they're

00:15:12.380 --> 00:15:15.110
going to be smarter than we are.

00:15:15.110 --> 00:15:19.550
It's a very dark picture of
what computing is going to be.

00:15:19.550 --> 00:15:22.760
And you all seen
2001-- the Hal computer

00:15:22.760 --> 00:15:25.310
in 2001, Space Odyssey?

00:15:25.310 --> 00:15:26.300
AUDIENCE: I know of it.

00:15:26.300 --> 00:15:27.758
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
You know of it.

00:15:27.758 --> 00:15:29.480
Well, shows my age.

00:15:29.480 --> 00:15:33.290
But that's the kind of vision,
this dark vision of computers

00:15:33.290 --> 00:15:35.390
taking over our lives.

00:15:35.390 --> 00:15:38.390
And that was alive and
well as early computing

00:15:38.390 --> 00:15:39.570
started to take off.

00:15:39.570 --> 00:15:41.810
And actually one of
the conceptualizers

00:15:41.810 --> 00:15:45.080
who got people worrying about
computing was Norbert Wiener.

00:15:45.080 --> 00:15:48.500
But along comes Licklider with
his background in psychology,

00:15:48.500 --> 00:15:52.130
and he has a completely
different vision.

00:15:52.130 --> 00:15:58.580
And his vision
wins, thank heavens.

00:15:58.580 --> 00:16:03.260
So he understands that
things like human perception,

00:16:03.260 --> 00:16:08.840
and goal-setting, and judgment,
and insight, and intuition--

00:16:08.840 --> 00:16:11.240
machines can't do
that, that these are

00:16:11.240 --> 00:16:13.735
incredible human attributes.

00:16:13.735 --> 00:16:15.110
And the machine's
just not can be

00:16:15.110 --> 00:16:18.590
able to equal us on that stuff,
that certain kind of feel

00:16:18.590 --> 00:16:23.460
we have about how things fall
together and shape up in place.

00:16:23.460 --> 00:16:25.820
So those qualities are
going to surpass machines,

00:16:25.820 --> 00:16:28.730
but then machines are going
to be able to do stuff

00:16:28.730 --> 00:16:31.220
that we can't do, that we're
not particularly good at,

00:16:31.220 --> 00:16:33.480
and don't want to
spend a lot of time on.

00:16:33.480 --> 00:16:35.510
So there's going to
be a relationship.

00:16:35.510 --> 00:16:39.740
So Licklider is spending a
lot of time at Lincoln Lab,

00:16:39.740 --> 00:16:43.940
playing on computers
up at Lincoln Lab.

00:16:43.940 --> 00:16:46.370
He starts to master all
those early machines,

00:16:46.370 --> 00:16:53.240
including the DEC PDP-8,
the first mini-computer--

00:16:53.240 --> 00:16:56.180
real mini-computer.

00:16:56.180 --> 00:17:00.830
He leads the MIT
Psychology Department,

00:17:00.830 --> 00:17:08.119
and joins BBN, which is the
premier acoustics consulting

00:17:08.119 --> 00:17:09.790
firm.

00:17:09.790 --> 00:17:13.520
And they do things like
design the acoustics

00:17:13.520 --> 00:17:16.910
for Lincoln Center, the
famous acoustics firm.

00:17:16.910 --> 00:17:19.160
And they had this
idea, gee, maybe

00:17:19.160 --> 00:17:21.770
we ought to get in the
computing business.

00:17:21.770 --> 00:17:24.710
Maybe these computers are
actually here to stay.

00:17:24.710 --> 00:17:29.630
So Licklider is hired
at BBN to bring them

00:17:29.630 --> 00:17:33.055
into the early computing age.

00:17:33.055 --> 00:17:34.055
And that's what he does.

00:17:37.950 --> 00:17:41.570
In this 1960 article,
his key image

00:17:41.570 --> 00:17:45.170
is a fig tree
pollinated by a wasp--

00:17:45.170 --> 00:17:47.390
in other words, the relationship
between the fig tree

00:17:47.390 --> 00:17:49.400
and the wasp is
complete symbiotic,

00:17:49.400 --> 00:17:51.860
they're mutually supporting.

00:17:51.860 --> 00:17:53.510
And that's the
vision that he has

00:17:53.510 --> 00:17:55.490
of what computing
is going to be.

00:17:55.490 --> 00:18:00.350
So it's this partnership
between computers and people

00:18:00.350 --> 00:18:03.440
with a complementary
set of functions.

00:18:03.440 --> 00:18:05.960
And the partnership
has to be in real time.

00:18:05.960 --> 00:18:08.270
We have to get rid of all
this batch processing stuff.

00:18:08.270 --> 00:18:10.250
That has to go.

00:18:10.250 --> 00:18:13.190
It's got to be real time.

00:18:13.190 --> 00:18:15.020
The computer is
to relieve people

00:18:15.020 --> 00:18:18.470
of that drudgery factor,
the 85% of the set up time

00:18:18.470 --> 00:18:21.470
we spend getting ready to think.

00:18:21.470 --> 00:18:26.600
It is a time of what is being
talked about as time-sharing.

00:18:26.600 --> 00:18:29.930
These big massive mainframes
behind glass with the priests

00:18:29.930 --> 00:18:32.900
and priestesses dressed
in white lab coats,

00:18:32.900 --> 00:18:35.780
people don't get access to them.

00:18:35.780 --> 00:18:39.290
It's like going to
the Oracle of Delphi.

00:18:39.290 --> 00:18:40.640
You just can't get in there.

00:18:40.640 --> 00:18:44.010
And he has a vision of
could we, in effect,

00:18:44.010 --> 00:18:46.820
take that computer back
from the Oracle of Delphi

00:18:46.820 --> 00:18:48.380
and get people on this thing.

00:18:48.380 --> 00:18:49.790
And how are we going to
do that with mainframes?

00:18:49.790 --> 00:18:52.123
We're going to do it through
what's called, at the time,

00:18:52.123 --> 00:18:52.790
time-sharing.

00:18:52.790 --> 00:18:56.420
Let people have access
to a share of time.

00:18:56.420 --> 00:19:01.000
And he has a vision of
central computers, and then--

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:05.080
as a competing center
with interconnected users

00:19:05.080 --> 00:19:07.300
tying into that central
computing system.

00:19:10.630 --> 00:19:14.920
He understands
things like building

00:19:14.920 --> 00:19:21.170
a network of people
aided by computers

00:19:21.170 --> 00:19:25.370
that become in effect a
network of thinking centers.

00:19:25.370 --> 00:19:29.660
And that network concept
really is a core idea

00:19:29.660 --> 00:19:33.460
that is what his team at
DARPA later establishes

00:19:33.460 --> 00:19:35.750
BBN as the internet.

00:19:35.750 --> 00:19:37.980
He understands that
artificial intelligence

00:19:37.980 --> 00:19:42.320
isn't an analogous way of
thinking about thinking--

00:19:42.320 --> 00:19:46.640
that it can help us understand
intellectual processes.

00:19:50.480 --> 00:19:54.320
He has a vision of a computer
being a desk console, not

00:19:54.320 --> 00:19:55.400
a mainframe--

00:19:55.400 --> 00:19:56.978
in other words,
radically smaller

00:19:56.978 --> 00:19:58.520
than even the
mini-computer that he's

00:19:58.520 --> 00:20:01.370
starting to play with from DEC.

00:20:04.130 --> 00:20:10.160
He just has a series of these
concepts in this 1960 article

00:20:10.160 --> 00:20:13.910
that lays out what's
going to be happening.

00:20:13.910 --> 00:20:17.150
He envisions
interactive computing.

00:20:17.150 --> 00:20:20.900
He envisions programming
is not just programming.

00:20:20.900 --> 00:20:24.590
He starts to understand
that this is a science--

00:20:24.590 --> 00:20:27.410
in a way, a linguistic
kind of science in itself,

00:20:27.410 --> 00:20:30.320
and is deserving full respect--

00:20:30.320 --> 00:20:34.370
that computer science is a true
science like other sciences,

00:20:34.370 --> 00:20:37.100
that it's not just
a new tool set.

00:20:37.100 --> 00:20:40.190
It's something organized
around one of the fundamentals.

00:20:40.190 --> 00:20:43.467
Information is one
of the fundamentals,

00:20:43.467 --> 00:20:45.800
one of the foundational
building blocks of the universe.

00:20:45.800 --> 00:20:48.230
And you're organizing a whole
field around information.

00:20:48.230 --> 00:20:50.030
Computing is going
to be a science,

00:20:50.030 --> 00:20:53.420
and he recognizes that
very, very early on,

00:20:53.420 --> 00:20:55.220
long before others.

00:20:55.220 --> 00:20:56.930
It'll have practical
applications,

00:20:56.930 --> 00:21:03.920
but it's worthy of a whole
intellectual field on its own.

00:21:03.920 --> 00:21:08.630
And he sees how
closely tied computing

00:21:08.630 --> 00:21:09.922
can be to cognitive science.

00:21:09.922 --> 00:21:12.380
So he has a whole vision of
what he calls dynamic modeling.

00:21:15.130 --> 00:21:17.100
In other words,
this is an era where

00:21:17.100 --> 00:21:20.010
you get statistics on paper.

00:21:20.010 --> 00:21:23.220
But he has the vision that, if
you put them on your computer,

00:21:23.220 --> 00:21:26.910
you can start to play
with each element

00:21:26.910 --> 00:21:32.040
and begin to turn them
into graphs and designs,

00:21:32.040 --> 00:21:36.540
and get a much more realistic
feel for how the data is

00:21:36.540 --> 00:21:40.260
related, and start to play
with the different variables.

00:21:40.260 --> 00:21:44.070
And you're going to be able
to feed hundreds and thousands

00:21:44.070 --> 00:21:46.470
of variables into
your computer in a way

00:21:46.470 --> 00:21:49.200
that you can never
even think of,

00:21:49.200 --> 00:21:53.830
when people are doing
statistics by pencil and paper.

00:21:53.830 --> 00:21:56.910
So he has a whole vision
of this whole-- what

00:21:56.910 --> 00:21:58.830
he calls dynamic
modeling, the modeling

00:21:58.830 --> 00:22:03.750
role that computing effect plays
in a very dramatic way now.

00:22:03.750 --> 00:22:09.960
It's that computing can handle
this problem of complexity

00:22:09.960 --> 00:22:12.210
because of its
relentless ability

00:22:12.210 --> 00:22:16.170
to deal with thousands and
now millions of variables.

00:22:16.170 --> 00:22:17.700
So economics is
a profession that

00:22:17.700 --> 00:22:20.190
was organized around
essentially you couldn't really

00:22:20.190 --> 00:22:23.280
handle much more than
three, four, five variables

00:22:23.280 --> 00:22:25.140
operating at the same time.

00:22:25.140 --> 00:22:27.870
Computing would
enable science to cope

00:22:27.870 --> 00:22:32.340
with a profound issue
like climate change,

00:22:32.340 --> 00:22:35.010
and actually start to
be able to model that.

00:22:35.010 --> 00:22:36.750
So he understands
all this stuff,

00:22:36.750 --> 00:22:40.740
and he starts to lay this out
piece after piece after piece

00:22:40.740 --> 00:22:42.280
for people to think about.

00:22:45.300 --> 00:22:48.510
I mentioned earlier
the electronic library.

00:22:48.510 --> 00:22:50.490
He understands that
all information

00:22:50.490 --> 00:22:52.217
is going to be online
and stored online,

00:22:52.217 --> 00:22:54.300
and is going to be accessible
to everybody who can

00:22:54.300 --> 00:22:58.170
get onto one of these things.

00:22:58.170 --> 00:23:00.480
And it will be
the library and it

00:23:00.480 --> 00:23:03.328
will be the reference
librarian for you.

00:23:03.328 --> 00:23:05.370
In other words, it's going
to be able to organize

00:23:05.370 --> 00:23:08.220
your information in ways
that could never have

00:23:08.220 --> 00:23:09.960
been previously anticipated.

00:23:14.820 --> 00:23:19.950
15 years before the PC and
30 years before the internet,

00:23:19.950 --> 00:23:24.510
he's seeing graphics,
computing graphics, computer

00:23:24.510 --> 00:23:29.220
rich personal workstations,
human computer symbiosis,

00:23:29.220 --> 00:23:32.220
interactive computing,
networks, the idea

00:23:32.220 --> 00:23:34.920
of an online community,
a thinking community,

00:23:34.920 --> 00:23:40.170
online libraries, instant
retrieval, data organization,

00:23:40.170 --> 00:23:43.800
computing language,
programming that's

00:23:43.800 --> 00:23:51.330
elevated from a tool
set to a true science--

00:23:51.330 --> 00:23:53.260
a whole digital
medium of expression.

00:23:53.260 --> 00:23:54.970
So he is a visionary.

00:23:54.970 --> 00:23:55.950
He has this vision.

00:23:58.740 --> 00:24:03.180
He starts writing about
the intergalactic network.

00:24:03.180 --> 00:24:08.940
It's the worldwide web decades
before Tim Berners-Lee here

00:24:08.940 --> 00:24:10.770
pulls it off.

00:24:10.770 --> 00:24:17.500
He's a visionary, and
of a remarkable degree.

00:24:17.500 --> 00:24:22.950
And there's no vision
champion at the time,

00:24:22.950 --> 00:24:27.990
but then DARPA
hires him out of BBN

00:24:27.990 --> 00:24:31.740
to lead essentially
this whole development

00:24:31.740 --> 00:24:33.330
of personal computing.

00:24:33.330 --> 00:24:39.240
So it's a completely rare
moment where a visionary becomes

00:24:39.240 --> 00:24:40.290
the vision enabler.

00:24:43.950 --> 00:24:45.450
What happens here?

00:24:45.450 --> 00:24:47.940
So 1957 is the Shock of Sputnik.

00:24:47.940 --> 00:24:50.340
So DARPA gets created.

00:24:50.340 --> 00:24:54.110
DARPA's originally given
the space mission, because.

00:24:54.110 --> 00:24:55.950
Eisenhower's angry
at the services

00:24:55.950 --> 00:24:59.010
because they weren't
talking to each other,

00:24:59.010 --> 00:25:02.460
and Russians got the
first satellite up.

00:25:02.460 --> 00:25:04.380
And it wasn't about a
nice blinking thing,

00:25:04.380 --> 00:25:08.002
it was about first strike
ballistic missile capability.

00:25:08.002 --> 00:25:08.835
It was very serious.

00:25:12.600 --> 00:25:15.570
But then he took space
away and gave it to NASA,

00:25:15.570 --> 00:25:17.910
so DARPA had to start
thinking of things to do.

00:25:17.910 --> 00:25:20.790
And they come up with a
lot of creative stuff,

00:25:20.790 --> 00:25:25.050
but the big early DARPA
set of accomplishments

00:25:25.050 --> 00:25:28.770
is really Licklider
and his team.

00:25:28.770 --> 00:25:35.040
And so Jack Kennedy
and Secretary

00:25:35.040 --> 00:25:38.410
of Defense Robert McNamara
go through the Cuban Missile

00:25:38.410 --> 00:25:42.600
Crisis, which is a
complete nightmare.

00:25:42.600 --> 00:25:46.230
And we do things like get
within 20 minutes of launching

00:25:46.230 --> 00:25:48.818
a first strike by mistake.

00:25:48.818 --> 00:25:50.610
And they realize that
they've got something

00:25:50.610 --> 00:25:54.780
that they call a really serious
command and control problem.

00:25:54.780 --> 00:25:57.720
And Jack Ruina, who's head
of DARPA, who's another MIT

00:25:57.720 --> 00:26:03.948
faculty member, hires
Licklider to come in and deal

00:26:03.948 --> 00:26:05.490
with the command
and control problem.

00:26:05.490 --> 00:26:09.030
And Licklider's response to
Jack Ruina is, wait a minute,

00:26:09.030 --> 00:26:15.270
I'm working on computing and
making computing personal.

00:26:15.270 --> 00:26:18.150
What do I know about the
command and control problem?

00:26:18.150 --> 00:26:20.940
But they have a
conversation, and Ruina

00:26:20.940 --> 00:26:23.640
starts to see that what
Licklider is working on

00:26:23.640 --> 00:26:26.650
is exactly what he is concerned
about the command and control

00:26:26.650 --> 00:26:27.150
problem.

00:26:27.150 --> 00:26:30.540
With all these capabilities that
Licklider is thinking about,

00:26:30.540 --> 00:26:33.510
they need to tackle this
command and control problem.

00:26:33.510 --> 00:26:36.930
So Licklider comes to
DARPA, and because he's

00:26:36.930 --> 00:26:39.540
working on what DARPA
calls a presidential--

00:26:39.540 --> 00:26:42.870
in other words, this is the
problem the president himself--

00:26:42.870 --> 00:26:45.090
President Kennedy
himself has posed--

00:26:45.090 --> 00:26:47.700
fix the command and
control problem.

00:26:47.700 --> 00:26:50.130
He has resources.

00:26:50.130 --> 00:26:53.400
So it's a very powerful moment.

00:26:53.400 --> 00:26:55.440
Ruina hadn't really
thought about the linkage

00:26:55.440 --> 00:26:57.600
between behavior and
computing and the kind of way

00:26:57.600 --> 00:27:00.240
that Licklider has
really thought through,

00:27:00.240 --> 00:27:02.370
but begins to see what
the possibilities are.

00:27:02.370 --> 00:27:06.330
So this is really when
DARPA becomes DARPA.

00:27:09.540 --> 00:27:17.307
Some of the culture of DARPA--
we've talked a bit about they--

00:27:17.307 --> 00:27:19.140
I'll just summarize
some of the rules sets--

00:27:28.600 --> 00:27:32.870
hire great program managers
that are world-class,

00:27:32.870 --> 00:27:34.880
give them an enormous
amount of power.

00:27:34.880 --> 00:27:37.430
They have the
authority at DARPA.

00:27:37.430 --> 00:27:40.340
Unleash them.

00:27:40.340 --> 00:27:43.400
Let them develop a
vision, and then find

00:27:43.400 --> 00:27:46.250
the best people in
the country to do it,

00:27:46.250 --> 00:27:48.500
and they're on the problem.

00:27:48.500 --> 00:27:50.590
That is not the way
R&D organizations are

00:27:50.590 --> 00:27:52.370
organized in the United States.

00:27:52.370 --> 00:27:55.220
That's not the way we do it.

00:27:55.220 --> 00:27:56.960
We have NSF.

00:27:56.960 --> 00:27:59.930
It has a program manager.

00:27:59.930 --> 00:28:04.820
The program manager is overseen
by a peer review system.

00:28:04.820 --> 00:28:07.670
They wait for applications to
come in from the scientists

00:28:07.670 --> 00:28:08.960
saying what they'd like to do.

00:28:08.960 --> 00:28:10.400
They review the applications.

00:28:10.400 --> 00:28:14.000
The peer review team makes a
decision on who gets funded.

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:15.830
The project manager
is essentially

00:28:15.830 --> 00:28:18.530
doing the arranging
here, but peer review

00:28:18.530 --> 00:28:19.880
makes the core decision.

00:28:19.880 --> 00:28:21.830
It's a much more
bureaucratic process,

00:28:21.830 --> 00:28:23.490
and it's a bottom-up system.

00:28:23.490 --> 00:28:25.490
Look, there's a lot of
strengths in that system.

00:28:25.490 --> 00:28:27.380
I don't want to
knock that system.

00:28:27.380 --> 00:28:29.600
It's an important function
to have for science

00:28:29.600 --> 00:28:32.480
so that scientists themselves
can originate ideas.

00:28:32.480 --> 00:28:33.880
That's not what DARPA does.

00:28:33.880 --> 00:28:35.540
DARPA has strong
program managers.

00:28:35.540 --> 00:28:40.610
They develop the ideas, and they
go out and make them happen.

00:28:40.610 --> 00:28:43.670
And program managers don't
last much more than four years

00:28:43.670 --> 00:28:44.200
at DARPA--

00:28:44.200 --> 00:28:46.530
three to five years--

00:28:46.530 --> 00:28:49.520
so they've got
that period of time

00:28:49.520 --> 00:28:53.720
to get done with their project.

00:28:53.720 --> 00:28:56.150
They've got to get something
happening within a relatively

00:28:56.150 --> 00:28:57.060
short period of time.

00:28:57.060 --> 00:28:59.330
So that's going to affect
what they try to do.

00:28:59.330 --> 00:29:02.120
They're not working on
25-year projects at DARPA.

00:29:02.120 --> 00:29:04.670
They're working on stuff that
can be stood up in a relatively

00:29:04.670 --> 00:29:06.410
short period of time.

00:29:06.410 --> 00:29:12.110
And it's just a very
different organizational model

00:29:12.110 --> 00:29:14.060
for a science organization--

00:29:14.060 --> 00:29:17.633
no peer review, two sign offs.

00:29:17.633 --> 00:29:20.300
If you're a program manager, you
figure out what you want to do,

00:29:20.300 --> 00:29:21.470
what direction
you want to go to.

00:29:21.470 --> 00:29:23.887
You sell that to your office
director and to the director,

00:29:23.887 --> 00:29:24.530
and that's it.

00:29:24.530 --> 00:29:27.710
And it could be funded that day.

00:29:27.710 --> 00:29:31.520
Can move very, very fast.

00:29:31.520 --> 00:29:35.990
So they're organized around this
whole grand challenge concept.

00:29:35.990 --> 00:29:38.090
DARPA doesn't want to
do incremental advance.

00:29:38.090 --> 00:29:41.210
It only wants to do technology
revolutionary breakthroughs

00:29:41.210 --> 00:29:43.940
that will change everything.

00:29:43.940 --> 00:29:45.160
So it doesn't want to waste--

00:29:45.160 --> 00:29:46.910
let other people do
the incremental stuff.

00:29:46.910 --> 00:29:48.800
That's not DARPA's job.

00:29:48.800 --> 00:29:50.332
And it's a right
left model, so it

00:29:50.332 --> 00:29:52.040
wants to look at what's
going to come out

00:29:52.040 --> 00:29:56.270
of the pipeline, what the
technology is that it wants--

00:29:56.270 --> 00:30:00.950
personal computing-- and then
go back into the pipeline

00:30:00.950 --> 00:30:03.830
and figure out the research
that's going to get this

00:30:03.830 --> 00:30:07.210
outcome, again, within the
life of the program manager--

00:30:07.210 --> 00:30:09.990
in this, say, four
or five-year period.

00:30:09.990 --> 00:30:16.270
So it's just it's
really different.

00:30:16.270 --> 00:30:20.300
Licklider pulls together
different teams.

00:30:20.300 --> 00:30:24.290
So the other thing
about DARPA is

00:30:24.290 --> 00:30:26.390
that essentially the role
of the program manager

00:30:26.390 --> 00:30:29.690
is to find great groups
and to support them.

00:30:29.690 --> 00:30:31.730
And that's what Licklider does.

00:30:31.730 --> 00:30:33.470
So DARPA's different
because it's

00:30:33.470 --> 00:30:37.670
working as an institutional
entity in the R&D space.

00:30:37.670 --> 00:30:41.610
It's another
institutional R&D entity,

00:30:41.610 --> 00:30:47.420
but it is also organized around
personal face-to-face great

00:30:47.420 --> 00:30:49.340
group creation.

00:30:49.340 --> 00:30:51.800
So it takes the two
sides of the equation

00:30:51.800 --> 00:30:54.740
that we treated as two
entirely different classes--

00:30:54.740 --> 00:30:56.270
it is putting them together.

00:30:56.270 --> 00:30:58.640
That's why DARPA follows
after our discussion

00:30:58.640 --> 00:30:59.930
in the great group class.

00:30:59.930 --> 00:31:02.540
That's who Licklider is finding.

00:31:02.540 --> 00:31:05.000
He's finding these
amazing, great groups.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:07.400
And we've seen some
of them before.

00:31:07.400 --> 00:31:13.040
These are all who's who of the
history of computer science.

00:31:13.040 --> 00:31:16.610
We talked about Doug Engelbart.

00:31:16.610 --> 00:31:18.040
There he is.

00:31:18.040 --> 00:31:22.520
He's someone that Lick
finds and supports,

00:31:22.520 --> 00:31:24.710
even though the Stanford
Research Institute

00:31:24.710 --> 00:31:26.040
doesn't know what he's doing.

00:31:26.040 --> 00:31:27.623
They don't know what
he's doing there.

00:31:30.380 --> 00:31:33.440
He does this you know
unbelievable demonstration

00:31:33.440 --> 00:31:36.620
with all this
breakthrough material.

00:31:36.620 --> 00:31:40.350
At MIT, project MAC is right
there at Technology Square.

00:31:40.350 --> 00:31:44.190
You can kind of recognize that
building on the lower left.

00:31:44.190 --> 00:31:49.130
So after Licklider leaves DARPA,
he goes to join Project MAC.

00:31:49.130 --> 00:31:53.780
But meanwhile, he gets stood
up by Ferdinand Corbato and Bob

00:31:53.780 --> 00:31:55.863
Fano.

00:31:55.863 --> 00:31:58.280
The history of what comes out
of that place-- and it's all

00:31:58.280 --> 00:32:01.400
DARPA-funded-- is
just breathtaking.

00:32:01.400 --> 00:32:05.780
So when you go buy that
building at Technology Square--

00:32:05.780 --> 00:32:08.060
I think it's 500
Technology Square--

00:32:08.060 --> 00:32:11.900
take off your hat,
because amazing stuff.

00:32:11.900 --> 00:32:14.450
Absolutely amazing
stuff occurred there.

00:32:14.450 --> 00:32:18.390
Within MIT, there's this
fascinating conflict.

00:32:18.390 --> 00:32:22.580
There are two competing
visions of computer science

00:32:22.580 --> 00:32:25.910
fighting for the
same DARPA money.

00:32:25.910 --> 00:32:29.990
So Marvin Minsky,
great roboticist--

00:32:29.990 --> 00:32:32.380
great, one of the all-time
greats-- just died recently.

00:32:32.380 --> 00:32:35.630
Amazing figure.

00:32:35.630 --> 00:32:38.120
Minsky had this vision that
computer thinking would be

00:32:38.120 --> 00:32:40.370
superior to people's thinking.

00:32:40.370 --> 00:32:44.420
So he has the Artificial
Intelligence Laboratory

00:32:44.420 --> 00:32:47.180
and he's running
that vision, and then

00:32:47.180 --> 00:32:49.820
Licklider and
Corbato and Fano are

00:32:49.820 --> 00:32:52.240
running the computer
is our friend,

00:32:52.240 --> 00:32:53.990
it's going to be a
symbiotic relationship,

00:32:53.990 --> 00:32:56.540
we're going to do
personal computing--

00:32:56.540 --> 00:33:00.650
very different ideas battling
each other for funding.

00:33:00.650 --> 00:33:05.000
It took years of negotiation
to put together CSAIL

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:08.810
because you had these two
different visions that

00:33:08.810 --> 00:33:11.010
competed with each other.

00:33:11.010 --> 00:33:16.850
Just like we talked about the
competition over the genome

00:33:16.850 --> 00:33:19.040
last week in the
great groups session,

00:33:19.040 --> 00:33:21.020
this was one of those
great competitions.

00:33:21.020 --> 00:33:24.130
Each side is pushing each other.

00:33:24.130 --> 00:33:28.040
And Minsky and team would do
unbelievable robotics stuff

00:33:28.040 --> 00:33:31.680
and they would say, top this.

00:33:31.680 --> 00:33:34.680
And the MAC team would come
back with the responses.

00:33:34.680 --> 00:33:37.470
So it was a wonderful
competition going on here.

00:33:37.470 --> 00:33:42.390
But creating CSAIL required two
co-directors at the outset--

00:33:42.390 --> 00:33:44.400
somebody from computer
science and somebody

00:33:44.400 --> 00:33:46.977
from artificial intelligence.

00:33:46.977 --> 00:33:48.060
It's kind of settled down.

00:33:48.060 --> 00:33:49.560
They're all on the
same project now.

00:33:49.560 --> 00:33:54.720
But that was a 20-year or
longer project to get there.

00:33:54.720 --> 00:34:01.500
So it's a remarkable
set of communities,

00:34:01.500 --> 00:34:05.310
including project MAC at MIT,
but that's just one of them

00:34:05.310 --> 00:34:06.160
that gets created.

00:34:06.160 --> 00:34:08.070
So all the early computer
science departments

00:34:08.070 --> 00:34:09.330
are funded by DARPA.

00:34:09.330 --> 00:34:10.679
DARPA really creates them.

00:34:10.679 --> 00:34:12.659
That's why there is
computer science that's

00:34:12.659 --> 00:34:14.242
so deep and rich in
the United States.

00:34:18.630 --> 00:34:25.489
Licklider's three research
priorities at DARPA are

00:34:25.489 --> 00:34:29.600
time-sharing-- which is
really interactive computing,

00:34:29.600 --> 00:34:31.370
and that's like
personal computing--

00:34:31.370 --> 00:34:33.800
and then graphics and modeling--

00:34:33.800 --> 00:34:35.540
and another great
name, Ivan Sullivan

00:34:35.540 --> 00:34:39.139
ran that piece, and that's
early computing graphics--

00:34:39.139 --> 00:34:41.420
and then networking.

00:34:41.420 --> 00:34:43.730
And Bob Taylor, who we
talked about last week,

00:34:43.730 --> 00:34:47.870
who goes to Xerox PARC, comes
out of DARPA to do that.

00:34:47.870 --> 00:34:49.940
And that's where
he gets his stuff.

00:34:49.940 --> 00:34:52.429
And he and Larry
Roberts, as well,

00:34:52.429 --> 00:34:56.900
are the ones that lead the
effort to stand up computing.

00:34:56.900 --> 00:34:59.480
And Luyao told us
about him last week.

00:34:59.480 --> 00:35:02.240
We sent around his obit, because
he just died this past week.

00:35:02.240 --> 00:35:03.410
It's a wonderful obit--

00:35:03.410 --> 00:35:04.910
if you all get a
chance to read it--

00:35:04.910 --> 00:35:07.790
that appeared in New York Times.

00:35:07.790 --> 00:35:11.730
The ARPANET gets created.

00:35:11.730 --> 00:35:14.270
So Licklider creates
this thing at DARPA.

00:35:14.270 --> 00:35:16.430
He has two different
stints at DARPA.

00:35:16.430 --> 00:35:18.890
He's there for several
years in each stint.

00:35:18.890 --> 00:35:21.948
But he creates a community that
keeps carrying on the projects.

00:35:21.948 --> 00:35:23.990
In other words, they agree
on what the agenda is,

00:35:23.990 --> 00:35:26.540
and they keep working
down the list together.

00:35:26.540 --> 00:35:30.110
So DARPA doesn't-- isn't
always able to do this.

00:35:30.110 --> 00:35:31.460
Often there's a real problem--

00:35:31.460 --> 00:35:33.470
when a program manager
leaves after their three

00:35:33.470 --> 00:35:36.950
to five-year stint, what
happens to their work?

00:35:36.950 --> 00:35:38.360
Who does the follow one?

00:35:38.360 --> 00:35:41.180
But Licklider builds
this community

00:35:41.180 --> 00:35:47.270
that keeps the project going for
way over a decade and a half.

00:35:47.270 --> 00:35:54.350
And Taylor and Larry
Roberts, out of Lincoln Lab,

00:35:54.350 --> 00:35:57.350
really lead the effort
to do the internet.

00:35:57.350 --> 00:36:05.160
They hire BBN, Licklider's old
firm, to actually carry it out.

00:36:05.160 --> 00:36:08.210
And that's done right
here in Cambridge.

00:36:08.210 --> 00:36:11.240
So the internet gets
done just up the road.

00:36:16.740 --> 00:36:20.420
I won't go into the whole
story about it, but it's--

00:36:24.920 --> 00:36:28.010
two great things occur in 1969--

00:36:28.010 --> 00:36:31.670
we go to the Moon and
we do the internet.

00:36:31.670 --> 00:36:37.430
And in 1969, nobody had
ever heard of the internet.

00:36:37.430 --> 00:36:42.830
But in the end, which
is the more significant?

00:36:42.830 --> 00:36:47.780
And that's going on
just up the street here.

00:36:47.780 --> 00:36:49.250
It's a pretty
breathtaking moment.

00:36:49.250 --> 00:36:51.290
These are some of the figures.

00:36:51.290 --> 00:36:57.110
This is Vint Cerf and
Bob Kahn, who were--

00:36:57.110 --> 00:36:59.580
lead the whole protocol effort--

00:36:59.580 --> 00:37:02.092
TCPIP, the whole
internet protocol system

00:37:02.092 --> 00:37:04.175
that's really at the heart
of the internet system.

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:10.670
Larry Roberts, who came
out of Lincoln Lab,

00:37:10.670 --> 00:37:18.050
persuades the DARPA
director to use email.

00:37:18.050 --> 00:37:20.290
So DARPA's like an
early email user.

00:37:20.290 --> 00:37:22.340
So everybody in
DARPA goes on email.

00:37:22.340 --> 00:37:25.430
They nurture this thing along.

00:37:25.430 --> 00:37:29.990
They're one of the
early user bases.

00:37:29.990 --> 00:37:31.830
It becomes this system
of communication,

00:37:31.830 --> 00:37:36.080
because DARPA's using it for
the entire ARPANET community.

00:37:36.080 --> 00:37:45.110
It's originally stood up with
about five universities linked.

00:37:45.110 --> 00:37:49.480
The real problem they've
got is that, because DARPA's

00:37:49.480 --> 00:37:51.980
trying to stand up these early
computer science departments,

00:37:51.980 --> 00:37:54.830
and lots of breakthroughs
are happening in computing,

00:37:54.830 --> 00:37:56.690
DARPA's having to
spend a fortune buying

00:37:56.690 --> 00:38:00.710
new computers for each one
of its university research

00:38:00.710 --> 00:38:01.220
centers.

00:38:01.220 --> 00:38:02.553
And it's costing them a fortune.

00:38:02.553 --> 00:38:06.050
They're spending their
money on the next generation

00:38:06.050 --> 00:38:07.910
of computer advance.

00:38:07.910 --> 00:38:12.140
And one of the reasons they
have to do the internet

00:38:12.140 --> 00:38:15.020
is that, gee, if they only
had to buy one computer

00:38:15.020 --> 00:38:17.698
and everybody
could get on it, it

00:38:17.698 --> 00:38:19.490
would be a gigantic
money saver, and they'd

00:38:19.490 --> 00:38:21.140
be able to do much more stuff.

00:38:21.140 --> 00:38:23.572
So they have this
internal reason.

00:38:23.572 --> 00:38:25.280
Now, the external
reason for the internet

00:38:25.280 --> 00:38:27.560
is much more complicated.

00:38:27.560 --> 00:38:29.260
One of the reasons
is that it's going

00:38:29.260 --> 00:38:32.840
to be a secure communications
system at the time

00:38:32.840 --> 00:38:33.890
of terrible threats.

00:38:33.890 --> 00:38:37.478
Now, you all are--

00:38:37.478 --> 00:38:39.020
probably don't have
much recollection

00:38:39.020 --> 00:38:41.720
of 9/11, but sure
enough, the only way

00:38:41.720 --> 00:38:46.080
we knew about each other on 9/11
was because the internet still

00:38:46.080 --> 00:38:46.580
worked.

00:38:46.580 --> 00:38:50.990
The phone system in New York
City went down in a flash.

00:38:50.990 --> 00:38:52.490
And it worked.

00:38:52.490 --> 00:38:55.700
It turned out to be an
enormously important

00:38:55.700 --> 00:38:59.630
fallback communications system,
because it is so resilient.

00:38:59.630 --> 00:39:02.810
In other word, you can establish
those network lines essentially

00:39:02.810 --> 00:39:07.610
through any connection, not
just a straight one-to-one

00:39:07.610 --> 00:39:09.750
connection like
the phone system.

00:39:09.750 --> 00:39:13.670
So that was part of the
rationale for developing

00:39:13.670 --> 00:39:17.950
the internet, but
frankly, Licklider

00:39:17.950 --> 00:39:20.577
had a vision of what the
internet was going to be,

00:39:20.577 --> 00:39:21.910
which is really why they did it.

00:39:21.910 --> 00:39:25.150
And then they had this excuse of
trying to reduce their computer

00:39:25.150 --> 00:39:27.592
budget for buying
fancy computers for all

00:39:27.592 --> 00:39:29.800
their computer science
departments around the country

00:39:29.800 --> 00:39:31.420
at universities.

00:39:31.420 --> 00:39:36.260
So it's an amazing story.

00:39:36.260 --> 00:39:38.530
We heard the story
from Luyao last week

00:39:38.530 --> 00:39:40.375
about how personal
computing comes about.

00:39:42.880 --> 00:39:46.480
A lot of that
community is being--

00:39:46.480 --> 00:39:51.070
came right out of Licklider's
support of university research

00:39:51.070 --> 00:40:02.560
groups, and then moves over
to carry it out at Xerox PARC.

00:40:02.560 --> 00:40:04.690
And then, of course, Xerox
PARC is unable to do it,

00:40:04.690 --> 00:40:07.210
as you explained.

00:40:07.210 --> 00:40:10.120
But luckily, Steve
Jobs buys the rights

00:40:10.120 --> 00:40:11.770
to walk through
and see the stuff.

00:40:11.770 --> 00:40:15.790
And he's a great implementer.

00:40:15.790 --> 00:40:17.130
All right.

00:40:17.130 --> 00:40:19.383
Steph, what did I miss?

00:40:19.383 --> 00:40:20.800
STEPH: The one
point that I really

00:40:20.800 --> 00:40:25.420
