00:47:45.440 --> 00:47:48.110
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: He is an
absolutely remarkable figure.

00:47:48.110 --> 00:47:54.350
And the core was this vision
that he had, and that--

00:47:57.330 --> 00:48:00.900
and this image of a crossover.

00:48:00.900 --> 00:48:04.080
Often, great technologies
are crossover technologies.

00:48:04.080 --> 00:48:11.790
When Jobs creates the iPod,
he's taking an MP3 player

00:48:11.790 --> 00:48:14.670
of high quality and
certain new attributes,

00:48:14.670 --> 00:48:17.460
but he's joining with
something entirely different--

00:48:17.460 --> 00:48:20.790
a remarkable way of
organizing the music industry.

00:48:20.790 --> 00:48:22.860
And it's two pieces that
get joined together,

00:48:22.860 --> 00:48:25.530
and that's at the
heart, I think,

00:48:25.530 --> 00:48:27.150
of what Licklider is able to do.

00:48:27.150 --> 00:48:30.390
He's able to take his
capability at computing

00:48:30.390 --> 00:48:32.460
and his engineering and
computing capabilities,

00:48:32.460 --> 00:48:34.965
but he crosses it with
his whole background

00:48:34.965 --> 00:48:37.620
and set of understandings that
he comes to with psychology.

00:48:37.620 --> 00:48:40.200
And it's that crossover
that makes him

00:48:40.200 --> 00:48:41.380
an absolutely unique figure.

00:48:41.380 --> 00:48:45.540
So when you all are thinking
about how to do great stuff,

00:48:45.540 --> 00:48:48.300
just keep that crossover idea.

00:48:48.300 --> 00:48:51.840
Bringing something from
here and moving it over here

00:48:51.840 --> 00:48:54.600
is really at the heart
of a tremendous amount

00:48:54.600 --> 00:48:55.290
of creativity.

00:48:55.290 --> 00:48:59.700
It may be the definition
of creativity.

00:48:59.700 --> 00:49:02.250
It's what he pulls off.

00:49:02.250 --> 00:49:05.880
By the time Licklider
finishes his second stint--

00:49:05.880 --> 00:49:10.332
which he's not as happy at
DARPA the second time around.

00:49:10.332 --> 00:49:12.540
He has a director that
doesn't get along with as well

00:49:12.540 --> 00:49:15.180
as he did with Jack Ruina and
another famous DARPA director,

00:49:15.180 --> 00:49:16.020
named Heilmeier--

00:49:18.800 --> 00:49:19.890
Heilmeier, excuse me.

00:49:24.540 --> 00:49:27.150
That team of has worked
their way through those three

00:49:27.150 --> 00:49:30.270
critical projects.

00:49:30.270 --> 00:49:32.880
They've done the
internet by '69.

00:49:32.880 --> 00:49:36.690
They've done desktop
computing, carried out

00:49:36.690 --> 00:49:41.580
with some DARPA support by
largely ex-DARPA funded folks

00:49:41.580 --> 00:49:43.020
at Xerox PARC.

00:49:43.020 --> 00:49:45.870
And then they've done computer
graphics, and a lot of that

00:49:45.870 --> 00:49:49.050
moves over to Xerox PARC,
as well, and then from there

00:49:49.050 --> 00:49:50.340
to Apple.

00:49:50.340 --> 00:49:54.155
But they've worked their
way through those pieces.

00:49:54.155 --> 00:49:55.905
Let me just mention
the film here briefly.

00:50:00.060 --> 00:50:03.590
Rasheed, you can-- we'll
get to this in a second,

00:50:03.590 --> 00:50:06.800
although we'll let Steph
do a couple more questions.

00:50:06.800 --> 00:50:09.890
The film was this
desperate attempt

00:50:09.890 --> 00:50:11.870
by these people who have
created the internet.

00:50:11.870 --> 00:50:13.250
And you saw them.

00:50:13.250 --> 00:50:15.200
This is an amazing collection.

00:50:15.200 --> 00:50:16.850
A lot of on the film.

00:50:16.850 --> 00:50:19.380
Larry Roberts is there;
and Frank Hart, who

00:50:19.380 --> 00:50:23.010
led the BBN team; and Bob
Kahn, who's on the BBN team,

00:50:23.010 --> 00:50:26.720
then goes to DARPA and works
with Vint Cerf on the TCPIP

00:50:26.720 --> 00:50:31.610
internet protocol system;
and Paul Baran who

00:50:31.610 --> 00:50:33.620
has a vision for what--
how to put together

00:50:33.620 --> 00:50:36.350
the whole packet switching
system to begin with,

00:50:36.350 --> 00:50:38.750
that's at the core
of the internet.

00:50:38.750 --> 00:50:41.690
All these famous
internet pioneers

00:50:41.690 --> 00:50:45.480
are all put together on the
film, and they're desperate.

00:50:45.480 --> 00:50:49.340
They are desperate because
the internet has only

00:50:49.340 --> 00:50:52.530
gone to about 50 different
university computer science

00:50:52.530 --> 00:50:53.030
departments.

00:50:53.030 --> 00:50:55.370
And they realize that they've
got this earth-shattering

00:50:55.370 --> 00:50:58.550
communication system, and
they're trying to explain

00:50:58.550 --> 00:51:01.220
desperately to--

00:51:01.220 --> 00:51:04.760
on a 16-millimeter film
what they've accomplished.

00:51:08.900 --> 00:51:11.270
I think it's '72
they do the film.

00:51:11.270 --> 00:51:15.860
It's not until really 1993, 1994
that the internet completely

00:51:15.860 --> 00:51:16.730
scales up.

00:51:16.730 --> 00:51:20.330
So it's a long hiatus.

00:51:20.330 --> 00:51:23.850
And NSF actually plays a
very, very important role

00:51:23.850 --> 00:51:28.760
in the scale up, because it gets
turned over by DARPA and NSF--

00:51:28.760 --> 00:51:33.650
and NSF under Erich Bloch, who
is the only NSF director who

00:51:33.650 --> 00:51:34.850
came out of industry.

00:51:34.850 --> 00:51:41.180
So Erich Bloch was one of the
leaders of the IBM 360 project

00:51:41.180 --> 00:51:43.127
and was a winner
of the president's

00:51:43.127 --> 00:51:45.210
Medal of Technology, but
he was an IBM officially.

00:51:45.210 --> 00:51:46.760
Wasn't a scientist.

00:51:46.760 --> 00:51:49.790
So he gets leadership
of NSF, and he

00:51:49.790 --> 00:51:55.160
creates NSF's very strong
computing organization,

00:51:55.160 --> 00:52:00.320
pulls one of the leaders
of deck to run it.

00:52:00.320 --> 00:52:03.110
And they treat computing
as a full science.

00:52:03.110 --> 00:52:05.650
That's another moment
in Licklider's vision

00:52:05.650 --> 00:52:07.460
is when NSF starts
to treat computer

00:52:07.460 --> 00:52:09.500
science as a true
science, not just

00:52:09.500 --> 00:52:12.945
a nice tool for other
scientists to play with.

00:52:12.945 --> 00:52:14.570
So that's a pretty
critical moment too.

00:52:14.570 --> 00:52:18.980
And Erich Bloch and some
others understand the power

00:52:18.980 --> 00:52:20.570
of the internet
as a communication

00:52:20.570 --> 00:52:23.240
system in science, and then
they spread it to universities

00:52:23.240 --> 00:52:24.320
all over the place.

00:52:24.320 --> 00:52:27.950
That creates a fabulous early
audience, and then it scales.

00:52:27.950 --> 00:52:30.500
So that's kind of
what plays out there.

00:52:30.500 --> 00:52:33.530
But it's a remarkable--

00:52:33.530 --> 00:52:36.770
another remarkable is
part of the story here.

00:52:36.770 --> 00:52:39.085
Steph, let's go to a
question or two more.

00:52:39.085 --> 00:52:39.627
STEPH: Great.

00:52:39.627 --> 00:52:43.260
I have precisely
two more questions,

00:52:43.260 --> 00:52:49.590
the first is with
a sentiment that

00:52:49.590 --> 00:52:52.767
was shared in the last couple
of pages in the reading.

