capabilities are used

00:53:00.300 --> 00:53:03.120
is much a matter of cultural
choice and historical accident

00:53:03.120 --> 00:53:05.620
as it's politics or fashion."

00:53:05.620 --> 00:53:10.050
And I think back to maybe the
first or the second course

00:53:10.050 --> 00:53:13.080
where we began to reflect
about the role of culture

00:53:13.080 --> 00:53:15.780
and technology transfer
and technology adoption,

00:53:15.780 --> 00:53:19.200
and in thinking about the sort
of functionalist ethics that we

00:53:19.200 --> 00:53:21.300
might have-- this
is by Amartya Sen--

00:53:21.300 --> 00:53:23.520
he's a very famous economists
who came out of India

00:53:23.520 --> 00:53:26.370
in developmental economics--

00:53:26.370 --> 00:53:31.380
and thinking about the ways in
which we're evaluating vision.

00:53:31.380 --> 00:53:35.530
And it seems-- and I have a
couple of notes here from which

00:53:35.530 --> 00:53:37.120
I will read--

00:53:37.120 --> 00:53:41.440
that many of the people
who we have truly

00:53:41.440 --> 00:53:45.130
regarded as innovators and
as transformative members

00:53:45.130 --> 00:53:47.650
of society have
created things that

00:53:47.650 --> 00:53:49.390
are effectively public goods.

00:53:49.390 --> 00:53:51.760
They've really approached
technology and engineering

00:53:51.760 --> 00:53:54.400
from a utility ethics
framework-- not so

00:53:54.400 --> 00:53:56.830
much about having that
bias to commercialization,

00:53:56.830 --> 00:53:58.600
like maybe Steve
Jobs did, but it

00:53:58.600 --> 00:54:01.450
was the Lickliders and the
Edisons who really thought

00:54:01.450 --> 00:54:03.940
about how they could
create a product that

00:54:03.940 --> 00:54:06.445
was going to transform
society for everyone.

00:54:06.445 --> 00:54:09.070
It wasn't going to be a product
that was going to be accessible

00:54:09.070 --> 00:54:10.570
only to the few.

00:54:10.570 --> 00:54:14.530
And so in thinking about our
ethics of commercialization

00:54:14.530 --> 00:54:18.520
today, perhaps I
thought it would

00:54:18.520 --> 00:54:21.070
be worth it to become a little
philosophical, in the sense

00:54:21.070 --> 00:54:23.860
that Licklider was very
philosophical about the role

00:54:23.860 --> 00:54:26.650
that technology played in
the development of society--

00:54:26.650 --> 00:54:29.440
and ask ourselves about the ways
in which our commercialization

00:54:29.440 --> 00:54:31.990
bias may be precluding
us from creating

00:54:31.990 --> 00:54:33.610
the so-called
disruptive inventions

00:54:33.610 --> 00:54:34.887
that we still wish to pursue.

00:54:39.408 --> 00:54:41.200
RASHEED: So I think
this is a cool question

00:54:41.200 --> 00:54:43.650
because you get to do both--

00:54:43.650 --> 00:54:47.260
bring in, just like you said,
a lot of the cultural aspects

00:54:47.260 --> 00:54:50.810
that might be overlooked when
you have this commercialization

00:54:50.810 --> 00:54:52.570
bias.

00:54:52.570 --> 00:54:54.460
But I'm not sure--

00:54:54.460 --> 00:54:57.210
or in this context, I think
Licklider's got a head up

00:54:57.210 --> 00:54:58.768
because the field is wide open.

00:54:58.768 --> 00:55:01.060
And so nobody's really thought
about personal computing

00:55:01.060 --> 00:55:02.935
before, so he gets to
really define the field

00:55:02.935 --> 00:55:05.340
and make it general enough
so that it can be applicable

00:55:05.340 --> 00:55:05.840
everywhere.

00:55:05.840 --> 00:55:08.913
But in every sense, you get
the idea that-- time-sharing

00:55:08.913 --> 00:55:10.330
and all these
things-- he's trying

00:55:10.330 --> 00:55:14.020
to make computing a
lot more accessible.

00:55:14.020 --> 00:55:16.690
And so I think that's a really
cool and seminal thought

00:55:16.690 --> 00:55:18.880
to make things more
accessible, and that'll

00:55:18.880 --> 00:55:22.570
give you the innovative,
transformative, and really

00:55:22.570 --> 00:55:26.470
disruptive ideals-- to bring
this technology from one

00:55:26.470 --> 00:55:28.570
and spread it around.

00:55:28.570 --> 00:55:30.550
And so the spreading
effect, I'm not

00:55:30.550 --> 00:55:34.500
sure how to quantify
it like Licklider

00:55:34.500 --> 00:55:38.320
did, but I'm interested in what
projects that DARPA might be

00:55:38.320 --> 00:55:39.910
running now or
might be looking at,

00:55:39.910 --> 00:55:42.760
to see if there's still those
people within the organization

00:55:42.760 --> 00:55:46.090
that are looking at bringing
technologies that might exist

00:55:46.090 --> 00:55:49.480
now that might just be
[INAUDIBLE] or high risk,

00:55:49.480 --> 00:55:52.570
and spreading that to
a more normative phase,

00:55:52.570 --> 00:55:54.692
maybe like Licklider did.

