because there's a very strong
culture in computing, including

00:56:02.840 --> 00:56:06.050
a very strong culture
in MIT computing,

00:56:06.050 --> 00:56:08.510
that computing should
be free, and computing

00:56:08.510 --> 00:56:11.630
should be in the commons, and
computing should serve us all.

00:56:11.630 --> 00:56:16.430
And that's actually a very
strong ethos that, in a way--

00:56:16.430 --> 00:56:18.620
and I think it's your point--

00:56:18.620 --> 00:56:22.610
comes out of the way
in which Licklider

00:56:22.610 --> 00:56:25.700
and that remarkable team
evolved this technology.

00:56:25.700 --> 00:56:29.840
Because this is not a
for-profit operation.

00:56:29.840 --> 00:56:35.470
They are essentially
trying to spring

00:56:35.470 --> 00:56:38.920
a transformative
technology onto the world

00:56:38.920 --> 00:56:42.565
by building it in the
commons, and creating it

00:56:42.565 --> 00:56:45.340
into the commons, and making
it universally accessible.

00:56:45.340 --> 00:56:47.350
That's a remarkable project.

00:56:47.350 --> 00:56:48.820
That's not normally
the way we do

00:56:48.820 --> 00:56:53.350
stuff in a capitalist country.

00:56:53.350 --> 00:56:55.410
You've identified an
interesting kind of strand

00:56:55.410 --> 00:56:58.990
here that's a different kind of
technology development story.

00:56:58.990 --> 00:57:01.750
And it's a different story
than the Edison story.

00:57:07.180 --> 00:57:09.640
It enables, Martin,
as you point out,

00:57:09.640 --> 00:57:12.940
Gates and Jobs to
get extremely rich.

00:57:12.940 --> 00:57:16.000
But all the
foundational stuff was

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:17.920
thrown into the commons
long ahead of them,

00:57:17.920 --> 00:57:21.580
which was an enabler
for them, as well.

00:57:21.580 --> 00:57:22.720
So interesting.

00:57:22.720 --> 00:57:24.310
Thanks for bringing
the philosophy in.

00:57:24.310 --> 00:57:29.140
STEPH: [INAUDIBLE] for
