the other side of stealth.

01:13:21.850 --> 01:13:24.175
The military is a legacy sector.

01:13:26.700 --> 01:13:28.440
It's been around since 1787.

01:13:28.440 --> 01:13:30.570
It's extremely
resistant to change.

01:13:30.570 --> 01:13:32.880
It has its routines
and doctrines,

01:13:32.880 --> 01:13:38.190
and it has its doctrines
that govern how it fights

01:13:38.190 --> 01:13:39.040
and so forth.

01:13:39.040 --> 01:13:43.470
And then here are Perry,
and Brown, and DARPA

01:13:43.470 --> 01:13:45.360
landing in the
middle, forcing them

01:13:45.360 --> 01:13:48.480
to adopt completely
disruptive technologies

01:13:48.480 --> 01:13:50.910
from what they've been doing.

01:13:50.910 --> 01:13:55.050
So DARPA's operating here as
a change agent within a legacy

01:13:55.050 --> 01:13:56.490
sector military.

01:13:56.490 --> 01:14:01.080
It's able to do the change
agent role because of the island

01:14:01.080 --> 01:14:02.630
bridge model.

01:14:02.630 --> 01:14:06.180
Remember, we talked
about this at Xerox PARC.

01:14:06.180 --> 01:14:11.700
DARPA's got a bridge to
the Secretary of Defense,

01:14:11.700 --> 01:14:13.650
and the Secretary of
Defense is able to make

01:14:13.650 --> 01:14:16.950
it stick with the military.

01:14:16.950 --> 01:14:20.460
And that's a really
key DARPA capability.

01:14:20.460 --> 01:14:23.520
That's also a lesson
about how to bring change

01:14:23.520 --> 01:14:25.620
into legacy sectors.

01:14:25.620 --> 01:14:30.570
So DARPA rules of
small and flexible,

01:14:30.570 --> 01:14:32.550
and it's a flat
organization, and it

01:14:32.550 --> 01:14:34.620
allows a lot of
freedom and autonomy

01:14:34.620 --> 01:14:37.800
outside bureaucratic impediments
to its program managers.

01:14:37.800 --> 01:14:41.400
And it has an incredibly
talented technical staff,

01:14:41.400 --> 01:14:44.490
and it works off
the challenge model.

01:14:44.490 --> 01:14:46.830
The end of a project is
the end of the project.

01:14:46.830 --> 01:14:48.490
DARPA shuts things down.

01:14:48.490 --> 01:14:50.460
It just doesn't
persevere forever.

01:14:50.460 --> 01:14:54.870
If it doesn't seem to be
working, it'll close it down.

01:14:54.870 --> 01:15:02.380
It's got all those rules
sets, but in addition, it's

01:15:02.380 --> 01:15:04.510
got some other
capabilities that I

01:15:04.510 --> 01:15:07.120
think are important to
understanding how to bring

01:15:07.120 --> 01:15:08.920
change into legacy sectors.

01:15:11.590 --> 01:15:15.520
Form critical innovation
institutions--

01:15:15.520 --> 01:15:17.920
that's a lesson that
we're seeing here.

01:15:17.920 --> 01:15:19.870
The Defense Department
would not have

01:15:19.870 --> 01:15:22.540
done the revolution
in military affairs

01:15:22.540 --> 01:15:25.420
if there wasn't a critical
innovation system there

01:15:25.420 --> 01:15:27.970
to do the innovation, ie DARPA.

01:15:27.970 --> 01:15:31.450
So that's kind of a new rule
for us to think about right.

01:15:31.450 --> 01:15:33.760
What's going to be that
critical innovation system that

01:15:33.760 --> 01:15:36.700
can operate as a change agent?

01:15:36.700 --> 01:15:40.750
Because most of the
economy is legacy sectors.

01:15:40.750 --> 01:15:43.600
Point two, use this
island-bridge model.

01:15:43.600 --> 01:15:44.980
It's really critical.

01:15:44.980 --> 01:15:47.860
Remember, Edison can
call up JP Morgan

01:15:47.860 --> 01:15:51.880
and get JP Morgan to fund
the electrical system.

01:15:51.880 --> 01:15:53.960
That island-bridge thing
is absolutely critical.

01:15:53.960 --> 01:15:57.015
Get your innovation team
on a protected island,

01:15:57.015 --> 01:15:58.390
make sure they
have a route back.

01:15:58.390 --> 01:16:01.330
And DARPA's a great
example of that.

01:16:01.330 --> 01:16:03.400
Build a thinking community--

01:16:03.400 --> 01:16:06.100
that's what the
Licklider story is about.

01:16:06.100 --> 01:16:08.420
This is not just
Licklider having a vision.

01:16:08.420 --> 01:16:12.430
He's able to create a whole
thought community within DARPA

01:16:12.430 --> 01:16:14.710
and then by all the people
that are working for DARPA,

01:16:14.710 --> 01:16:18.850
like Doug angle and that
whole world out there.

01:16:18.850 --> 01:16:21.225
So they're able to scale
up this community so

01:16:21.225 --> 01:16:22.850
that it reaches a
certain kind of mass,

01:16:22.850 --> 01:16:25.183
and it can get a lot of stuff
done and a lot of thinking

01:16:25.183 --> 01:16:27.408
done, and develop a lot
and nurture a lot of ideas.

01:16:27.408 --> 01:16:29.950
So when you're thinking about
implementing your technologies,

01:16:29.950 --> 01:16:32.830
think about building
that thinking community.

01:16:32.830 --> 01:16:35.980
And then another key piece here
is linking the technologies

01:16:35.980 --> 01:16:38.690
to the operators.

01:16:38.690 --> 01:16:41.717
So if the technologists are
only talking to themselves

01:16:41.717 --> 01:16:43.300
and they are not
talking to the people

01:16:43.300 --> 01:16:46.790
actually operating the
system, nothing will happen.

01:16:46.790 --> 01:16:48.460
So you've got to
make sure, as you're

01:16:48.460 --> 01:16:50.770
working on bringing
your technologies about,

01:16:50.770 --> 01:16:54.110
that you've got linkages
to the actual operators.

01:16:54.110 --> 01:16:57.418
So these are a few more
lessons from DARPA.

