01:27:35.000 --> 01:27:39.040
and the first year, really
people are just making--

01:27:39.040 --> 01:27:40.930
including stuff that
they've already done,

01:27:40.930 --> 01:27:46.480
or even inflating what
they've accomplished

01:27:46.480 --> 01:27:47.620
to look good on the report.

01:27:47.620 --> 01:27:49.630
So those are the
only experiences

01:27:49.630 --> 01:27:53.550
that I've had is with
those two funding agencies.

01:27:53.550 --> 01:27:57.012
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I think DARPA
has the more [INAUDIBLE]

01:27:57.012 --> 01:27:59.220
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Yeah,
DARPA runs a different kind

01:27:59.220 --> 01:28:00.970
of opposite operation.

01:28:00.970 --> 01:28:05.970
There's there's, frankly, less
paper, but the DARPA program

01:28:05.970 --> 01:28:08.730
manager--

01:28:08.730 --> 01:28:12.970
at a traditional science agency,
the whole decision process

01:28:12.970 --> 01:28:16.940
is organized around whether or
not you get the grant award.

01:28:16.940 --> 01:28:19.958
And it's getting that
award out the door.

01:28:19.958 --> 01:28:22.250
That's how these organizations
are really put together.

01:28:22.250 --> 01:28:24.470
That's what the peer review
process and selection

01:28:24.470 --> 01:28:26.720
process is built around.

01:28:26.720 --> 01:28:28.840
In DARPA, and in the--

01:28:28.840 --> 01:28:31.750
excuse me-- in some
of the DARPA clones,

01:28:31.750 --> 01:28:36.260
the program manager, that's like
just getting the grant award.

01:28:36.260 --> 01:28:37.700
That's only stage one.

01:28:37.700 --> 01:28:40.970
Then the program manager
moves into your home.

01:28:40.970 --> 01:28:43.250
They're going to be
on you all the time.

01:28:43.250 --> 01:28:46.670
Someone has described
DARPA as a set of geniuses

01:28:46.670 --> 01:28:48.350
connected by a travel agent.

01:28:48.350 --> 01:28:50.960
They spend at least 1/3
of their time on the road

01:28:50.960 --> 01:28:57.080
out meeting with their
teams, bringing ideas around.

01:28:57.080 --> 01:28:59.840
They'll typically have a
number of teams standing up

01:28:59.840 --> 01:29:02.690
working on a portfolio
of related projects,

01:29:02.690 --> 01:29:05.330
and they're going to bring ideas
from those different teams.

01:29:05.330 --> 01:29:07.997
They're going to put those teams
together to talk to each other,

01:29:07.997 --> 01:29:10.310
and sometimes that's not
easy, because they don't want

01:29:10.310 --> 01:29:12.380
to really share their secrets.

01:29:12.380 --> 01:29:14.370
So it's a complicated
process to manage,

01:29:14.370 --> 01:29:18.200
but the DARPA manager
is there to help

01:29:18.200 --> 01:29:20.960
the awardee get
through the process

01:29:20.960 --> 01:29:23.690
and work in any way possible
to expedite things and move

01:29:23.690 --> 01:29:24.540
things along.

01:29:24.540 --> 01:29:27.800
So it's a completely
different organizational model

01:29:27.800 --> 01:29:31.100
for the program manager compared
to most science agencies.

01:29:31.100 --> 01:29:33.380
And the DARPA clones,
like ARPA-E or IARPA

01:29:33.380 --> 01:29:35.690
do the same thing.

01:29:35.690 --> 01:29:38.420
And we'll talk about
ARPA-E at a later class.

01:29:38.420 --> 01:29:41.280
But it's just a different model.

01:29:41.280 --> 01:29:47.210
And there's another capability--
we talked earlier about DARPA

01:29:47.210 --> 01:29:50.750
capability of working at
both the institutional level

01:29:50.750 --> 01:29:53.690
and at the great groups level.

01:29:53.690 --> 01:29:56.600
The purpose of this
reading about its work

01:29:56.600 --> 01:29:59.720
within the defense
legacy sector is

01:29:59.720 --> 01:30:02.510
to say that DARPA has
been able to do innovation

01:30:02.510 --> 01:30:06.360
within a legacy sector
to a remarkable degree,

01:30:06.360 --> 01:30:09.830
as well as do
innovation, like in IT,

01:30:09.830 --> 01:30:12.770
on a complete
technology frontier.

01:30:12.770 --> 01:30:16.700
That's a remarkable
set of capabilities

01:30:16.700 --> 01:30:20.330
to build into one
place, and yet its model

01:30:20.330 --> 01:30:22.730
has been able to fit both.

01:30:22.730 --> 01:30:25.820
So it's another
interesting achievement

01:30:25.820 --> 01:30:28.170
that it's been able to pull off.

01:30:28.170 --> 01:30:29.420
AUDIENCE: Just to go back to--

01:30:29.420 --> 01:30:31.030
