01:33:29.885 --> 01:33:31.760
He's like, look at this
cool thing I'm doing.

01:33:31.760 --> 01:33:33.718
Because they're kind of
in a different sectors.

01:33:33.718 --> 01:33:35.780
So he's like, check it out.

01:33:35.780 --> 01:33:36.530
What do you think?

01:33:36.530 --> 01:33:37.560
Because he's trying
to impress his friend,

01:33:37.560 --> 01:33:39.170
who's also very successful.

01:33:39.170 --> 01:33:43.387
And Gates is like, whoa,
this is pretty great.

01:33:43.387 --> 01:33:45.470
And then he goes and he
copies, and he [INAUDIBLE]

01:33:45.470 --> 01:33:46.690
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: You're
talking about Windows?

01:33:46.690 --> 01:33:47.315
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:33:47.315 --> 01:33:48.570
So he comes out with--

01:33:48.570 --> 01:33:49.375
was it Windows DOS?

01:33:49.375 --> 01:33:51.500
He comes out with that
right before [INAUDIBLE]----

01:33:51.500 --> 01:33:53.530
because this is going to be
part of the new Apple Computer.

01:33:53.530 --> 01:33:55.113
And he comes out
with it right before,

01:33:55.113 --> 01:33:57.780
so it looks like Gates
did it, instead of Jobs.

01:33:57.780 --> 01:33:59.810
And then Jobs literally
goes like, we're done.

01:34:02.690 --> 01:34:04.717
This is the reason Apple
became so secretive.

01:34:04.717 --> 01:34:06.050
They used to be a lot more open.

01:34:06.050 --> 01:34:08.840
They became secretive because
after that, he's like--

01:34:08.840 --> 01:34:11.412
any little thing can go
out if somebody finds out,

01:34:11.412 --> 01:34:12.620
we're not doing this anymore.

01:34:12.620 --> 01:34:15.380
So it completely
switched the hierarchy.

01:34:15.380 --> 01:34:18.410
So that's the rights
part, in terms of the--

01:34:18.410 --> 01:34:21.640
Jobs does it, and then
when Gates copies--

01:34:21.640 --> 01:34:24.470
when Jobs takes
Gates to court, Gates

01:34:24.470 --> 01:34:28.130
can say, actually, we both
stole it, but it's OK for him,

01:34:28.130 --> 01:34:29.750
so it's OK for me.

01:34:29.750 --> 01:34:30.320
[INAUDIBLE]

01:34:30.320 --> 01:34:32.570
RASHEED: But like you just
said, Jobs didn't steal it.

01:34:32.570 --> 01:34:34.560
He paid for it.

01:34:34.560 --> 01:34:36.380
He paid for the rights.

01:34:36.380 --> 01:34:38.060
AUDIENCE: When they
go to court, Gates

01:34:38.060 --> 01:34:40.910
says, yeah, we both just
took it from the same source.

01:34:40.910 --> 01:34:42.590
It's not like it was
originally Apple's.

01:34:42.590 --> 01:34:45.350
So that's the element
of the legality.

01:34:45.350 --> 01:34:46.940
The second part--
the reason PARC

01:34:46.940 --> 01:34:49.107
wouldn't do it is because
you have this thing called

01:34:49.107 --> 01:34:52.640
the innovator's dilemma,
which is, in any company,

01:34:52.640 --> 01:34:55.910
you can have a product line--
a great example's Kodak.

01:34:55.910 --> 01:34:58.250
They came out with the
first digital camera,

01:34:58.250 --> 01:35:00.650
but you're already
making so much money,

01:35:00.650 --> 01:35:05.180
and you probably have a
large revenue streams doing--

01:35:05.180 --> 01:35:06.860
taking pictures of Polaroids.

01:35:06.860 --> 01:35:08.860
So this is like, if you're
an Ethernet company--

01:35:08.860 --> 01:35:11.510
if you're 3Com, and
you have these--

01:35:11.510 --> 01:35:13.010
you're putting wires everywhere.

01:35:13.010 --> 01:35:15.430
It's not the next
day it's like, yo, we

01:35:15.430 --> 01:35:16.640
got to take all this out.

01:35:19.658 --> 01:35:21.950
Another thing too is, once
you become a public company,

01:35:21.950 --> 01:35:23.600
every single quarter matters.

01:35:23.600 --> 01:35:24.770
So you can never go back.

01:35:27.282 --> 01:35:29.490
You can know you're wrong
but you have to go forward,

01:35:29.490 --> 01:35:30.620
or else you're just
going to get kicked off

01:35:30.620 --> 01:35:32.900
or you're going to get
sued by shareholders.

01:35:32.900 --> 01:35:35.320
It's a very complicated
thing to do.

01:35:35.320 --> 01:35:37.985
RASHEED: Also, I wonder how
much PARC staff or Xerox staff

01:35:37.985 --> 01:35:40.610
there is left to really benefit
after all the staff is actually

01:35:40.610 --> 01:35:43.190
just going to Apple and
Microsoft afterward.

01:35:43.190 --> 01:35:47.673
It's not that I didn't
benefit because I was at Xerox

01:35:47.673 --> 01:35:48.590
and I missed the wave.

01:35:48.590 --> 01:35:49.090
It's like.

01:35:49.090 --> 01:35:51.547
I just left Xerox to go
work at Apple or Microsoft,

01:35:51.547 --> 01:35:52.880
and then got the benefits later.

01:35:52.880 --> 01:35:55.338
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: So Luyao,
you led us through Xerox PARC

01:35:55.338 --> 01:35:56.390
very nicely last week.

01:35:56.390 --> 01:36:00.680
Do you have thoughts on
how come Xerox didn't

01:36:00.680 --> 01:36:03.470
get the Alto, and
personal computing,

01:36:03.470 --> 01:36:07.520
and graphic interfaces,
and the mouse out the door?

01:36:07.520 --> 01:36:08.300
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:36:08.300 --> 01:36:11.390
[INAUDIBLE] last
week that they were

01:36:11.390 --> 01:36:13.800
so much into the research
they're doing, and so

01:36:13.800 --> 01:36:17.080
passion that they
didn't consider

01:36:17.080 --> 01:36:21.940
commercializing or bringing it
to the general audience at all.

01:36:24.620 --> 01:36:29.110
One of the investors came
to their meeting room

01:36:29.110 --> 01:36:34.060
and sat on a beanbag saying,
OK, I'm the person [INAUDIBLE]

01:36:34.060 --> 01:36:39.353
Can you guys show me more, and
I will commercialize all this

01:36:39.353 --> 01:36:40.270
by making it possible?

01:36:40.270 --> 01:36:41.440
But they didn't.

01:36:41.440 --> 01:36:43.300
They totally ignored him.

01:36:43.300 --> 01:36:46.390
So I think they had a
chance, but they just

01:36:46.390 --> 01:36:47.830
didn't the awareness, I think.

01:36:47.830 --> 01:36:48.913
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Right.

01:36:48.913 --> 01:36:51.000
It was a really serious
island-bridge connection

01:36:51.000 --> 01:36:51.815
problem.

01:36:51.815 --> 01:36:55.780
AUDIENCE: They were probably
missing one or two [INAUDIBLE]

01:36:55.780 --> 01:36:59.500
in their group that
were able to connect

01:36:59.500 --> 01:37:01.752
with the market with
their innovations.

01:37:01.752 --> 01:37:03.210
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
Part of this is

01:37:03.210 --> 01:37:04.690
something Martin
mentioned earlier,

01:37:04.690 --> 01:37:07.440
which is Xerox was focused
on its core competency, which

01:37:07.440 --> 01:37:09.960
is photocopies.

01:37:09.960 --> 01:37:15.180
And they didn't understand this
explosion of personal computing

01:37:15.180 --> 01:37:17.550
capability, because it didn't
fit their core competency

01:37:17.550 --> 01:37:18.750
model.

01:37:18.750 --> 01:37:26.130
So they missed a
staggering opportunity.

01:37:26.130 --> 01:37:29.100
But fortunately, Jobs saved
us, so it all worked out.

01:37:29.100 --> 01:37:32.513
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] call
it the beanbag effect.

01:37:32.513 --> 01:37:34.680
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Too
much time in those beanbags,

01:37:34.680 --> 01:37:36.930
is that your point, Lily?

01:37:36.930 --> 01:37:38.490
Right, that was a
great photograph

01:37:38.490 --> 01:37:39.900
of the crowd on beanbags.

01:37:39.900 --> 01:37:44.370
You had a great
picture for us, Luyao.

01:37:44.370 --> 01:37:47.230
How about a closing
thought, Max, on Fong--

01:37:47.230 --> 01:37:49.390
or a couple of closing thoughts?

01:37:49.390 --> 01:37:52.390
AUDIENCE: Let's see.

01:37:52.390 --> 01:37:53.850
How about a closing question?

01:37:53.850 --> 01:37:54.420
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Sure.

01:37:54.420 --> 01:37:54.770
AUDIENCE: All right.

01:37:54.770 --> 01:37:56.445
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: That's fine.

01:37:56.445 --> 01:37:58.415
I only let you get one
out, so it's all yours.

01:37:58.415 --> 01:37:59.790
AUDIENCE: So one
of the questions

01:37:59.790 --> 01:38:03.540
that someone had previously
mentioned this basically

01:38:03.540 --> 01:38:05.790
there's this stereotype that
government bureaucracy is

01:38:05.790 --> 01:38:08.970
kind of slow, and sluggish,
and full of red tape,

01:38:08.970 --> 01:38:11.190
and it's horrible.

01:38:11.190 --> 01:38:13.860
And is it possible
that you could use--

01:38:13.860 --> 01:38:15.450
like DARPA as an
example-- to say

01:38:15.450 --> 01:38:19.920
that maybe this is unfounded,
maybe it's not as realistic

01:38:19.920 --> 01:38:21.770
as people think?

01:38:21.770 --> 01:38:23.770
And to continue that--
there's a couple of parts

01:38:23.770 --> 01:38:26.490
to this question--
is it unfounded,

01:38:26.490 --> 01:38:32.880
and should the government
try to redo its image,

01:38:32.880 --> 01:38:35.550
for lack of a better phrase?

01:38:35.550 --> 01:38:38.750
And is there really any
advantage they can get from it?

01:38:38.750 --> 01:38:40.750
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:38:40.750 --> 01:38:41.400
AUDIENCE: What?

01:38:41.400 --> 01:38:43.033
Can you repeat [INAUDIBLE]

01:38:43.033 --> 01:38:43.950
AUDIENCE: Yeah, sorry.

01:38:43.950 --> 01:38:45.617
I know, I started
rambling a little bit.

01:38:48.210 --> 01:38:51.600
Is the government slow?

01:38:51.600 --> 01:38:54.240
AUDIENCE: Is DARPA an
instance where it's not slow?

01:38:54.240 --> 01:38:56.040
AUDIENCE: Yes.

01:38:56.040 --> 01:38:58.410
And does the government
get any advantage

01:38:58.410 --> 01:39:02.490
from making itself
not look slow?

01:39:02.490 --> 01:39:04.880
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: That's a
really important point, Max.

01:39:04.880 --> 01:39:10.350
DARPA is stuck in one of the
most notorious bureaucracies

01:39:10.350 --> 01:39:15.540
on the planet, that
dates back to like 1787.

01:39:15.540 --> 01:39:18.480
So how is it able
to do this stuff?

01:39:18.480 --> 01:39:22.110
It has some very interesting
rules and some capabilities

01:39:22.110 --> 01:39:22.650
that it got.

01:39:22.650 --> 01:39:27.600
One of its key rules is that--

01:39:27.600 --> 01:39:31.020
it's called other
transactions authority.

01:39:31.020 --> 01:39:37.260
And DARPA's argument is, look,
we're not buying jet aircraft.

01:39:37.260 --> 01:39:40.823
We're just buying what's in
people's heads to do research.

01:39:40.823 --> 01:39:42.240
So we don't have
to go through all

01:39:42.240 --> 01:39:43.980
that elaborate
procurement process

01:39:43.980 --> 01:39:46.140
to protect the taxpayers.

01:39:46.140 --> 01:39:48.780
We're out of the Federal
Procurement System.

01:39:48.780 --> 01:39:52.320
So DARPA's able to contract
with enormous freedom,

01:39:52.320 --> 01:39:54.540
and very quickly.

01:39:54.540 --> 01:39:58.890
And then another DARPA
power that they've acquired

01:39:58.890 --> 01:40:00.010
is that they can--

01:40:00.010 --> 01:40:02.700
they have what's
called IPA authority--

01:40:02.700 --> 01:40:05.880
Intergovernmental
Personnel Act authority.

01:40:05.880 --> 01:40:08.580
So ironically, at
one point, DARPA

01:40:08.580 --> 01:40:12.750
was attempting to hire me.

01:40:12.750 --> 01:40:14.900
And I don't know
why they wanted me,

01:40:14.900 --> 01:40:18.510
because I'm not a technologist,
but they seemed to want this.

01:40:18.510 --> 01:40:21.448
And I wasn't going
to go to DARPA,

01:40:21.448 --> 01:40:22.740
because I'm not a technologist.

01:40:22.740 --> 01:40:25.080
I wouldn't be at the
heart of the operation.

01:40:25.080 --> 01:40:27.000
So it wasn't going to work.

01:40:27.000 --> 01:40:29.580
But they said they
can hire me in a day.

01:40:29.580 --> 01:40:31.410
They said, you want to do this?

01:40:31.410 --> 01:40:32.820
You're on tomorrow.

01:40:32.820 --> 01:40:36.870
This Intergovernmental
Personnel Act

01:40:36.870 --> 01:40:39.120
enables them
essentially to enter

01:40:39.120 --> 01:40:42.720
into a contract with
whatever organization

01:40:42.720 --> 01:40:45.270
you're working for--
maybe it's a university.

01:40:45.270 --> 01:40:49.890
They buy your services using
this other transactions

01:40:49.890 --> 01:40:52.380
authority, so that they
can put you on the job

01:40:52.380 --> 01:40:53.640
almost immediately.

01:40:55.140 --> 01:40:59.550
The use this IPA authority with
companies or with universities

01:40:59.550 --> 01:41:03.060
to be able to hire in
lickety-split time.

01:41:03.060 --> 01:41:07.230
Corporations can't hire this
fast, much less universities,

01:41:07.230 --> 01:41:08.970
much less government.

01:41:08.970 --> 01:41:14.250
So they're outside of two
of the traditional banes

01:41:14.250 --> 01:41:16.680
of governmental
bureaucratic nightmares.

01:41:16.680 --> 01:41:20.220
They got themselves
free of that authority.

01:41:20.220 --> 01:41:25.590
And interestingly, both ARPA-E
and IARPA, the DARPA clones,

01:41:25.590 --> 01:41:29.200
have the same capabilities.

01:41:29.200 --> 01:41:32.232
So that's part of why they're
able to act like this.

01:41:32.232 --> 01:41:33.690
I don't think it's
the whole story,

01:41:33.690 --> 01:41:35.250
but that's a couple
of pieces that they've

01:41:35.250 --> 01:41:36.210
been able to acquire.

01:41:39.480 --> 01:41:41.592
RASHEED: I would
answer and say, I

01:41:41.592 --> 01:41:43.050
guess, traditionally,
you would say

01:41:43.050 --> 01:41:45.980
government and bureaucracy
[INAUDIBLE] the highlight

01:41:45.980 --> 01:41:46.740
of what's slow is.

01:41:46.740 --> 01:41:48.115
When you think of
something slow,

01:41:48.115 --> 01:41:51.330
you think of a congressional
session or something like that.

01:41:51.330 --> 01:41:52.680
STEPH: It's deliberate.

01:41:52.680 --> 01:41:54.097
RASHEED: And it's
deliberately so,

01:41:54.097 --> 01:41:56.347
and then there's an entire
argument that can get into.

01:41:56.347 --> 01:41:57.900
Is government
supposed to move slow

01:41:57.900 --> 01:42:00.540
because they need to be this
giant political machine that

01:42:00.540 --> 01:42:04.710
shouldn't be swayed by just
one charismatic convincing guy?

01:42:04.710 --> 01:42:07.080
But anyway, I think it's
important to understand

01:42:07.080 --> 01:42:09.545
that DARPA doesn't move
slow because often it

01:42:09.545 --> 01:42:10.920
doesn't have this
opportunity to,

01:42:10.920 --> 01:42:12.870
for national security reasons.

01:42:12.870 --> 01:42:17.340
It's just not prudent for
us to move slow to develop,

01:42:17.340 --> 01:42:19.570
I guess, like drones
and things like that,

01:42:19.570 --> 01:42:23.075
which might have been drastic--

01:42:23.075 --> 01:42:24.700
things would look
drastically different

01:42:24.700 --> 01:42:26.117
if someone else
had done it first,

01:42:26.117 --> 01:42:28.860
or if we went into the Gulf
War without these capabilities.

01:42:28.860 --> 01:42:31.430
STEPH: Transferring that example
to something like genomics,

01:42:31.430 --> 01:42:33.360
could you imagine the
kinds of implications

01:42:33.360 --> 01:42:39.210
that it could have on just
fundamental human ethics

01:42:39.210 --> 01:42:42.035
if they were able to create
genetic engineering overnight

01:42:42.035 --> 01:42:44.160
in the way that DARPA's
been able to create things?

01:42:46.002 --> 01:42:47.460
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
Well, I do want

01:42:47.460 --> 01:42:50.040
to tell you that DARPA
now has a very strong

01:42:50.040 --> 01:42:52.920
biological technologies office.

01:42:52.920 --> 01:42:55.800
So look out, Steph.

01:42:55.800 --> 01:42:59.423
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:42:59.423 --> 01:43:00.090
STEPH: Oh, yeah.

01:43:00.090 --> 01:43:02.460
Well, it was interesting,
because at the AAAS meeting

01:43:02.460 --> 01:43:06.270
in February, one of the sessions
that I went to-- actually with

01:43:06.270 --> 01:43:09.570
Chuck Weiss, who is
Bill's co-author for many

01:43:09.570 --> 01:43:11.400
of the things--

01:43:11.400 --> 01:43:14.760
was a panel that included this
guy named Gary Marchant who's

01:43:14.760 --> 01:43:19.770
a lawyer ethicist and genomics
engineer, who was talking

01:43:19.770 --> 01:43:22.890
about the necessity to
include a participatory ethics

01:43:22.890 --> 01:43:25.770
in decision making for genomics.

01:43:25.770 --> 01:43:28.260
And one of his primary
arguments, as I recall it,

01:43:28.260 --> 01:43:30.960
is truly that, if
we want to have--

01:43:30.960 --> 01:43:33.690
if we want to do a good
job of implementing this

01:43:33.690 --> 01:43:36.000
at scale, nationally
or globally,

01:43:36.000 --> 01:43:39.150
we also have to do a good
job of listening meaningfully

01:43:39.150 --> 01:43:41.280
to populations and
then, at the same time,

01:43:41.280 --> 01:43:46.350
meaningfully incorporating their
feedback into their creation

01:43:46.350 --> 01:43:46.890
process.

01:43:46.890 --> 01:43:49.380
And that's very difficult. And
I think that's precisely why

01:43:49.380 --> 01:43:51.960
government is slow-- or the
word that I choose use--

01:43:51.960 --> 01:43:55.530
deliberate-- but it obviously
does make innovation.

01:43:55.530 --> 01:43:59.070
So to Max's point, I don't
think that DARPA applies,

01:43:59.070 --> 01:44:01.550
unfortunately, to most things.